<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / Companies in clash over Skoda shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SPLIT has developed between the Volkswagen-controlled company that is
taking over imports of Czech-built Skoda cars to the UK and Skoda (GB),
which has handled them for the past 27 years.
Skoda (GB), owned by Motokov, the former Czechoslovak state foreign trade
organisation - itself being privatised - is refusing to allow its 250
dealers to sign contracts with the new company, Skoda Automobile UK, while
negotiations continue on whether Skoda (GB) should continue to play an
operational role in the import and distribution of the cars.
About 10,000 Skodas are sold in the UK each year.
Mr David Wilks, of Skoda (GB), said yesterday the company had expected that
the import and preparation centre it had operated for many years in Kings
Lynn, Norfolk, would continue to process the cars under contract to Skoda
Automobile UK.
Instead, VW is planning to set up its own import and distribution
arrangements, in keeping with its intention to expand Skoda sales greatly.
It hopes to quadruple sales - to 40,000 a year - by as early as 1996.
VW already has management control of the Czech manufacturer and is building
a 70 per cent stake.
Skoda (GB), while refusing to release dealers from their franchise
contracts, said it had temporarily freed them from their obligation to buy
cars exclusively from Skoda (GB) - in effect allowing them to take supplies
from the new company while negotiations continue and when Skoda Automobile
UK starts making its own shipments.
With the UK new car market still in recession, most dealers are believed to
have sufficient stocks to last through protracted negotiations.
The cooling in relations between the two sides comes as a setback after 13
months of mainly amicable negotiations over the transition.
More than 29 Skoda (GB) personnel have already transferred to the new
company. However, the impasse over the Kings Lynn import centre has led to
44 people being made redundant there.
Skoda Automobile UK formally took over as the UK importer on January 1 and
is a wholly owned subsidiary of Skoda Automobilova. VW already holds 31 per
cent, with the balance in the hands of the Czech government.
Its managing director, Mr Robin Woolcock, is a former managing director of
MAN Volkswagen Truck and Bus, the UK importer of Volkswagen and MAN
commercial vehicles.
Mr Woolcock has been managing the negotiations with Skoda (GB) and the
creation of the new company, which has just set up offices in Milton Keynes.
The expected leap in sales is based on a significant investment programme
for Skoda vehicles.
The DM8bn (Pounds 3.3bn) programme will lead to new models and is designed
to more than double Skoda's capacity to 460,000 cars a year by the mid
1990s.
</TEXT>
