<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / Circulation of The European rises to 200,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN newspaper is about to enter its second year of non-Maxwell
ownership with sales of about 200,000.
The international newspaper, which many expected would not long survive the
death of its founder and patron Robert Maxwell, was relaunched under the
ownership of the Barclay brothers on January 6 last year.
'We have increased sales week after week since,' said Mr Charles Garside,
editor of the weekly, which was losing about Pounds 1m a month under
Maxwell.
The newspaper's period of crisis after Maxwell's death severely affected its
complex distribution system, and Mr Garside believes the paper has come from
80,000 to about 200,000 in the year, although official sales figures are not
available.
In May the paper was able to bring back its suspended third section Elan and
resume promotion.
Mr Garside said that the owners, Mr David and Mr Frederick Barclay, who live
in Monte Carlo and own hotels and shipping lines, are pleased with the
progress of their first newspaper.
The main growth in sales has come from France, Germany and Spain. Sales in
the UK account for about a third of the total, although that proportion is
declining.
Mr Garside would not disclose details of the newspaper's financial
performance but said that all newspapers take about four years to break into
profit. The European is now 2 1/2 years old.
'We have a more than a good chance of making it work in the not-too-distant
future,' Mr Garside said.
He is also encouraged by the number of his newspaper's reports that are
being followed up each week by other newspapers.
</TEXT>
