<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / Motive sought for 'contract' murder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLICE investigating the killing of Mr Donald Urquhart, a London property
consultant, were still searching for a motive yesterday.
Detectives were making inquiries in the Marylebone area of London's West End
where Mr Urquhart, 55, was shot on Saturday night by a man who escaped on a
motorcycle.
The businessman had property dealings through a company called Bellgap and
was part-owner of the Elstree Golf Club at Borehamwood, Hertfordshire.
Police are convinced that the shooting was the work of a professional
killer.
Mr Urquhart was with his Thai-born girlfriend Miss Pat Iamspithone when he
was attacked near his penthouse home in Nottingham Street on Saturday night.
The gunman, wearing a crash helmet, shot Mr Urquhart in the head with a
revolver at close range. Mr Urquhart died three hours later in hospital.
Police were also examining files stored in Mr Urquhart's car, a stretched
Rover 827, which he used as a mobile office.
Mr Urquhart, who told business colleagues he started work as a hod carrier
on a building site, built up his fortune during the property boom of the
1970s and 1980s. He had connections abroad with tax havens such as Jersey in
the Channel Islands.
Detective Superintendent Bill Scholes, heading the investigating, said:
'This murder has all the hallmarks of a professional killing, by which I
mean somebody has been paid to do it, and it's been very professionally
carried out.'
Scotland Yard said: 'We are attempting to unravel Mr Urquhart's finances.
There is no evidence to suggest he was involved in anything illegal.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
