<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / Bleak midwinter
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The first snow of the winter in the Yorkshire coalfields covers the
stockpiles at Sharlston Colliery, near Wakefield, one of the pits threatened
with closure.
Opposition to the pit closure programme will be stepped up tomorrow when
mining unions meet the TUC to plan the next stage in their campaign. The
National Union of Mineworkers, the pit deputies' union Nacods and the
British Association of Colliery Management will hold talks with the
emergency committee set up by the TUC to campaign for jobs and economic
recovery.
The mining unions will later meet rail unions to 'discuss developments'
since they last met in October, just after British Coal announced its plan
to close 31 pits with the loss of 30,000 jobs.
The unions want to keep pressure on the government after the pre-Christmas
High Court ruling that the closure programme was unlawful.
The talks at the TUC will be followed by a meeting of the TUC
public-services committee to discuss opposition to the government's 1.5 per
cent ceiling on public-sector pay rises this year.
</TEXT>
