<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Copper, tin and nickel prices began 1993 on a strong note at the London
Metal Exchange. The COPPER market ended at the highest level for three
months in a follow through to last week's move above Dollars 2,300 a tonne.
Yesterday traders noted good Chinese buying and some suggested that today's
LME warehouse stocks figures might show a fall. Sentiment was also buoyed by
news of a 2.1 per cent rise in US construction spending in November, which
continued a recent wave of positive data from the world's major economy. The
three month copper price closed Pounds 39.75 up at Pounds 1,577.75 a tonne.
Copper's bullish mood spilled over into NICKEL up Dollars 214.50 to Dollars
6,237.50 a tonne for three months delivery, and TIN, up Dollars 157.50 to
Dollars 6,002.50 at tonne, although conditions in both markets were
described as thin. At the London Futures and Options Exchange the March
robusta COFFEE futures position surrendered its New Year's Eve rally to
close Dollars 11 down at Dollars 1,012 a tonne after trade selling in New
York had put the market on the defensive.
Compiled from Reuters
