FT  05 JAN 93 / International Capital Markets: Equity issues in Canada
raised CDollars 13bn last year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DESPITE the recession and a sluggish stock market, equity issues in Canada
raised more than CDollars 13bn (USDollars 10bn) last year, compared with
CDollars 8.9bn in 1991.
The 1992 total included CDollars 11.8bn in common share issues, including
both primary and secondary financings. The oil and gas sector was most
active, because of increasing exploration and development, and other
resource sectors were also busy.
Privatisation accounted for one large financing, a CDollars 850m issue of
Nova Scotia Power shares.
For the first nine months, new issues totalled CDollars 5.1bn against
CDollars 5.7bn a year earlier, the Investment Dealers Association of Canada
said. Underwriting revenues ran higher for brokers and the large investment
bankers. RBC Dominion Securities led the field in underwriting.
