<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / Alfred McAlpine buys civil engineering side of AF Budge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALFRED McALPINE yesterday bought the civil engineering businesses of AF
Budge, which went into receivership last month owing its bankers Pounds 20m.
Budge's 26 current road and bridge-building contracts - many of them large
infrastructural projects - will carry on under McAlpine and up to 250
on-site jobs will be saved.
The deal is likely to lift Alfred McAlpine back into the top five of
Britain's civil engineering contractors, alongside Tarmac, Balfour Beatty,
Amec and Birse. Alfred McAlpine was nearly always in the top five in the
first half of the 1980s but had fallen back in the past five years.
Budge will also fill in a hole in Alfred McAlpine's national spread, as it
is based in East Retford, Nottinghamshire, and is usually automatically
asked to bid for public works in the East Midlands and East Anglia, where
Alfred McAlpine has been weak.
Alfred McAlpine, which has headquarters at Hooton, Wirral, will keep the
East Retford offices going. It frequently bids for road-building work with
Amec, based nearby in Sandiway, Cheshire.
The Leeds office of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, which kept Budge trading with 197 job
losses after being appointed receiver, last night said it was close to
clinching the sale of Budge's building division.
The buyer is likely to be one of Kier, Ballast Needam, Try or Miller, all
identified in undisputed trade press reports, along with Alfred McAlpine, as
bidders for parts of the Budge business.
Mr Ken Lever, finance director of Alfred McAlpine, last night refused to
disclose the price of the Budge contracting business, claiming commercial
confidentiality relating to existing contracts.
However, it has to be less than Pounds 8.2m, which is 5 per cent of Alfred
McAlpine's net assets of Pounds 164m, the level above which disclosure would
have been compulsory under Stock Exchange rules.
The acquisition will raise Alfred McAlpine's payroll to about 4,500, of whom
1,100 are employed in the US. Alfred McAlpine will also assume liability for
about 80 recently completed Budge contracts, making good any defects.
Budge's ongoing contracts include work on the A41 at King's Langley for the
Department of Transport and the Black Country spine road.
