<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / Bosnia peace talks break off: Conference to resume after
factions have considered proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PEACE TALKS between the three warring factions in Bosnia broke up in
disagreement in Geneva last night, but will resume next Sunday after the
participants have consulted political and military colleagues on
constitutional and ceasefire proposals tabled by international mediators.
Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen, the co-chairmen of what have been described as
'the last chance' negotiations, said they would travel to Yugoslavia in the
next few days to pursue their quest for a peace settlement of the
nine-month-old conflict which has cost tens of thousands of lives. Mr Vance
said he would be seeing Mr Slobodan Milosevic, the Serbian president, in
Belgrade.
The first face-to-face talks between the Bosnian Moslem, Serb and Croatian
leaders since the start of the conflict began last Saturday in a
surprisingly positive atmosphere. But they adjourned last night without any
sign that deep differences between Bosnian Moslems and Serbs could be
resolved quickly.
After announcing that the co-chairmen had submitted two linked
constitutional and cessation of hostilities draft agreements to the
participants for signature, Mr Vance conceded that 'much remains to be
done'.
'We had hoped that all three would sign the documents we had prepared, but
the feeling among some of the participants was that they should go home and
consult', Mr Vance said. In the event, only one of the three
representatives, Mr Mate Boban, leader of the Bosnian Croat community,
signed both documents.
Mr Alija Izetbegovic, president of the Moslem-led Bosnian government, said
that while he approved proposals to create a sovereign, independent and
decentralised Bosnia-Hercegovina, he could not accept the map of the 10
provinces into which the country would be divided under the Vance-Owen plan.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, leader of the Bosnian Serbs, said he needed time to
consult with colleagues at home.
In practice, the territorial disagreements are less extensive than at first
appeared. Bosnian Serbs and Croats have already indicated they could agree
to an adjustment of disputed boundaries of some of the three provinces that
have been allocated to each ethnic group.
Apart from territorial questions, the main disagreements between the Bosnian
Moslems and Serbs is over the constitutional status of the future Serbian
provinces of Bosnia-Hercegovina.
The co-chairmen's proposals make clear that only the new state of
Bosnia-Hercegovina will have international legal status.
But Mr Karadzic is demanding the creation of an independent state within
Bosnia-Hercegovina, a solution incompatible with the Vance-Owen plan.
Royal Marines, due in Norway this month for an annual exercise, are being
placed on standby for Bosnia in a move described by UK defence officials as
'prudent contingency planning'.
Bosnia protagonists seek to dodge the blame, Page 2
</TEXT>
