<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / The Lex Column: Redland
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Redland had a busy end to 1992, judging by yesterday's string of disposals
and acquisitions. The net effect on earnings will be small, probably to
raise them only by around 1p per share which will not do much for dividend
cover. But the market understandably took heart from the signal that Redland
appears able to raise reasonable prices for those parts of the Steetley
acquisition which it either does not want or has had to divest for
competition policy reasons. Given the weak French economy, the Coverland
purchase may look oddly timed. This is a strategic opportunity, though, and
in the short run there should be margin benefits from rationalisation.
Recovery in the US and Australia and lower capital spending should make
Redland cash neutral in 1993. Together with reduced gearing from further
disposals, that should lift uncertainty over the 1993 dividend, making the
yield of just under 8 per cent attractive. This still assumes that German
housing remains unaffected by recession. Doubts on that score may remain
until well into the second half, limiting the follow-through to yesterday's
4 per cent advance.
</TEXT>
