<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, yesterday claimed that the Bank of
England's intervention to defend sterling on 'Black Wednesday' may have cost
the Treasury up to Pounds 1.7bn, Ivo Dawnay writes.
He demanded an independent inquiry into the events of September 16 when the
UK left the exchange rate mechanism. He said independent advisers had
calculated the figures based on interventions totalling Pounds 11bn to
Pounds 14bn.
Mr Brown released the figures to coincide with the three-month deadline for
the UK to repay the German authorities for their interventions in defence of
sterling.
He said: 'The extent of the loss could be as much as the whole budget for
trade and industry this financial year.'
