<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / More fathers given time off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of companies offering men paid time off from work when their
wives or partners have babies has increased dramatically in the past five
years, according to the Confederation of British Industry.
In 1987, only about 32 per cent of companies surveyed by the CBI gave
paternity leave on either a contractual or a discretionary basis. By last
year, that had risen to 76 per cent.
Most companies give two or three days for paternity leave, with a small
minority giving new fathers one or two weeks off.
By last year, 36 per cent of companies surveyed by the CBI were giving
paternity leave by contract, with a further 40 per cent giving it on a
discretionary basis.
The CBI says the service sector is much more likely to offer paternity leave
than manufacturers, with about 60 per cent of service companies offering it
on a contractual basis compared with 27 per cent of manufacturers.
According to Mr Steve Palmer, the CBI's deputy director of employment
affairs, the increase is partly explained by the increased interest that
employers and unions have been showing in non-wage issues as wage increases
have been squeezed during the recession.
The granting of paternity leave had also became a trend among more
progressive employers at the end of the 1980s.
The survey of time off also finds that companies are still more likely to
offer paid leave for military training, mainly for the Territorial Army,
than for paternity leave. The most common reason for discretionary time off
is bereavement, with 81 per cent of manufacturing companies offering two,
three or five days leave.
Although the service sector is usually more generous with discretionary
leave, the manufacturing sector does better with standard holidays. The CBI
estimates that half of all employees in manufacturing now get 25 days or
more a year compared with only 20 per cent in the service sector.
</TEXT>
