<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / Seoul predicts more trade deficit cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH KOREA cut its trade deficit almost in half to Dollars 4.92bn (Pounds
3.23bn) in 1992 and officials predict the deficit will shrink to Dollars
3.5bn this year.
Exports last year rose by 6.8 per cent to Dollars 76.8bn on a customs
clearance basis, while imports were almost unchanged at Dollars 81.7bn,
according to preliminary statistics from the Ministry of Trade and Industry.
The ministry estimates that exports will rise by 8 per cent to Dollars 83bn,
while imports will grow by 6 per cent to Dollars 86.5bn.
The expected growth in imports this year is because of increased purchase of
foreign machinery for plant automation and building supplies for several big
infrastructure projects.
Export growth last year was led by petrochemicals, steel, vehicles, tyres
and containers, while shipments of textiles, toys and footwear were sluggish
as the country's light industry lost competitiveness through higher wage
costs.
The trade deficit in 1991 reached a record Dollars 9.7bn.
</TEXT>
