FT  05 JAN 93 / Former ministers 'accused'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORMER senior Mexican ministers will be accused before a Los Angeles grand
jury of involvement in the torture and murder of Mr Enrique Camarena, an
official of the US Drug Enforcement Agency, according to the Mexican weekly
Proceso, Damian Fraser writes.
Mr Antonio Garate, an agent of the DEA investigating the Camarena murder,
told Proceso that Mr Manuel Bartlett, minister of interior from 1982-88 and
current governor of the state of Puebla, Mr Enrique Alvarez del Castillo,
former governor of Jalisco and attorney-general, and Mr Juan Arevalo, former
minister of national defence, would soon be formally accused.
The allegations against the three were made by prosecution witnesses in the
trial of Mr Humberto Alvarez Machain, acquitted on charges that he aided the
murder of Mr Camarena. All three have denied the claims.
The US attorney's office in Los Angeles yesterday said it was not in a
position to deny or confirm the report.
