<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / Kinkel set to become vice-chancellor: Rise of former civil
servant given added boost by Mollemann's resignation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR KLAUS KINKEL, the former top civil servant who shot into the political
limelight last year as German foreign minister, is set to become both
vice-chancellor in the ruling coalition and leader of the Free Democratic
Party.
He is confidently expected to declare himself as candidate for the FDP
leadership tomorrow, to succeed Mr Otto Lambsdorff, who retires later this
year. He will also be the party's candidate for the formal position of
vice-chancellor under Chancellor Helmut Kohl, in the wake of the sudden
resignation of Mr Jurgen Mollemann, the economics minister, on Sunday.
That was confirmed yesterday by Mr Hermann Otto Solms, parliamentary leader
of the FDP, as the junior partner in the coalition struggled to contain the
fall-out from the resignation. The party is fighting to hold on to the
economics portfolio in the government, in the face of calls from many parts
of German industry, and from other political parties, that the job should be
given to a serious expert.
Party officials insist that the ministry, which covers both industrial
policy, including most of the strategic planning for eastern Germany, and
external trade, should still go to a fully fledged politician, and not to an
outsider from the business community.
On the other hand, the main business lobbies want a competent expert who
also has the political influence necessary to put policies into action. They
also want a candidate who can work well with Mr Theo Waigel, the finance
minister, and not against him, as Mr Mollemann used to do.
Mr Dieter Vogel, government spokesman, suggested yesterday that Mr Kohl
would 'as a realistic politician' leave the choice of candidate up to the
FDP, which was given the portfolio in the coalition negotiations two years
ago.
The two names cited so far - Mr Gunter Rexrodt, who formerly held the
finance portfolio in Berlin, and Mr Walter Hirche, currently economics
minister in the state of Brandenburg - are both numerate, but no more than
provincial politicians. Both do, at least, have ample experience of the
problems of east Germany.
The whole upheaval leaves Mr Kinkel, who joined the FDP only two years ago,
as the one clear winner. For years a close associate and protege of Mr
Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the former foreign minister and honorary chairman of
the party, he has no grass-roots political experience, although he was
always a 'political' civil servant.
He had been agonising about whether to confirm his candidacy for the party
leadership, while remaining as foreign minister, but the demise of Mr
Mollemann leaves him little choice, and little opposition.
The only other alternative would be Mrs Irmgard Schwaetzer, the construction
minister, but she suffered a humiliating defeat last year in the contest
with Mr Kinkel to become foreign minister. Mr Kinkel is expected to announce
his candidacy tomorrow, at the traditional Epiphany rally of the party in
Stuttgart - appropriately enough in his home state of Baden-Wurttemberg.
Editorial comment, Page 15
</TEXT>
