<HEADLINE>
FT  05 JAN 93 / MacGregor pledges 'full speed ahead' for rail sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT signalled its determination last night to press ahead with
privatising Britain's railways, claiming the plans would create a better
service for passengers and freight customers.
Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, used a speech to his local
Conservative association in South Norfolk to hit back at recent suggestions
that the government's proposals were stalled and would have to be revised.
Rail privatisation was going 'full speed ahead', he told them.
As Labour called on the government to spell out 'how deep is their U-turn',
Mr MacGregor said recent criticism of plans for 'commercialising' British
Rail passenger services were based on 'complete misunderstandings'.
The government was aiming to 'inject into the railways more private sector
skills and resources', he said. 'Our proposals will make sure we get that
further improvement in service for passengers and freight which is so
necessary if we are to get the benefits of the record levels of capital
investment currently going into our railways.'
Speculation that the government was preparing to back down over its
proposals for BR intensified last week following prime minister John Major's
characterisation of them as a 'semi-privatisation'.
Last year's white paper proposed that only the freight operations would be
sold outright.
On the passenger side, the private sector would be asked to bid for
franchises to operate British Rail's trains, the contracts going to the
companies requiring the lowest subsidies. The infrastructure would remain in
state ownership, train operators being charged for the use of the tracks.
While acknowledging that BR was already carrying out 'important reforms' of
the railway system, Mr MacGregor criticised current service standards -
particularly in its freight operations.
'I don't find anyone who thinks that BR is providing a perfect service now
and does not need further change,' he said.
The transport secretary reiterated the government's pledge to continue
subsidies for 'socially necessary lines'.
He also emphasised that progress towards the planned franchising of BR's
passenger services would be gradual.
</TEXT>
