<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Life in the Single Market: From barricades to new frontiers
as Shell ponders the extremes - Predicting the future / Jim Gordon explains
the purpose of the oil group's long-term planning methods to Tony Jackson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN it comes to long-range thinking on big issues such as the future of
Europe, you can be sure of Shell.
Like other big oil companies, Shell plans its investments on a massive scale
stretching over the next 10 or 15 years. But for the real long term, it
relies on its own system of hypothetical world models, or scenarios.
These are in no sense predictions, says Mr Jim Gordon, Shell's European
co-ordinator. They are simply possible worlds, against which the company's
investment plans can be tested.
It is currently working on two of these world models. At one extreme is the
scenario it calls 'barricades'. The other is 'new frontiers'.
Barricades envisages a world dominated by competing trade blocs, one of them
presumably being Fortress Europe. There is free trade within the blocs,
protectionism between them.
New frontiers is an opposite world of trade without barriers, dominated by
the Gatt philosophy. Growth is faster, competition is keener and developing
countries grow more quickly than developed ones.
Either scenario, Mr Gordon says, would fundamentally affect the competitive
situation in Europe. Neither offers a particularly comfortable environment
for business to work in.
'Under the barricades scenario, one would assume that the prospect for
significant growth in the world economy is less. The trading blocs are still
large, and within that there will be quite fierce competition: you'll still
be fighting for your own home patch.
'In the case of new frontiers, there is growth, and through growth there is
investment opportunity, which helps you to survive. But the breakdown of
trade barriers gives rise to very real competitive forces on existing
players.'
The main thing to grasp about these scenarios, Mr Gordon says, is that
neither will actually happen.
'The big seduction of scenarios is that you use them to predict things with.
But they're not prediction models.'
So what are they for? 'To open up the mind of managers, such as myself, to
the possibility of real and significant change from the situation you're in
at the moment.
'When you're looking at your major strategic decisions, whether on projects
or the development of your people, they require long lead times. You test
the robustness of your basic assumptions against those rather different
conditions. So you avoid nice, linear extrapolations from the status quo.'
Let us take an example. At one extreme, the EC market might eventually end
up as unified as the US.
At the other, it could look more like the Balkans. What does the model say?
'You can describe it as looking like either. The thing about a scenario is
that it's supposed to be internally consistent. You're trying to describe
plausible worlds which could exist. Is there a fundamental incompatibility
between the general environment of the scenario and that assumption about
the political structure?'
Plainly, Mr Gordon has no intention of giving away what Shell really thinks.
There is a sound business reason for this.
The Shell method, the company believes, gives it a commercial edge. If it
published its expectations and everyone else followed suit, the exercise
would be self-defeating.
But he is prepared to offer a few thoughts on how Europe might develop in
the nearer term.
'It's your customer that determines the competitive climate more than
anything else. The single market brings with it a considerable enhancement
of consumer choice. It also increases the efficiency of the industrial and
economic process within Europe, which again is of direct benefit to the
customer.
'The single market means less bureaucracy, but very few of us in industry
would see that being of direct benefit to ourselves. In the main, the cost
savings will be passed on to the customer and add to the efficiency of the
economic process, which I think is a good thing.
'It also enhances the competitive climate in which European industries will
have to operate. National barriers will break down, both formally and
informally, in the sense that consumers become much more receptive to brands
and influences outside their traditional boundaries. So competition will
increase, which will make life tougher for European industry. That's not
necessarily a bad thing either.'
Part of the competition, of course, consists of uneconomic capacity from
eastern Europe. How long will this remain a problem?
'That varies a lot from industry to industry, but it'll probably take longer
rather than shorter. As we've seen from the rationalisation of some
industries in western Europe, it takes a long, long time for the cash cow
represented by these plants to dry up. And these east European industries do
two things besides: they provide employment, which governments are quite
correctly anxious to protect, and they are a source of foreign exchange.'
There are two other worries. First, how fast the single market will settle
down in reality.
'In legal formality, it's in place now. But the processes and checks to
ensure compliance with the legislation have still got to be tested.'
There is also a large question in Mr Gordon's mind about the kind of profit
margins available in the newly competitive single market, and whether
companies - Shell, British Steel or BASF, for instance - have low enough
overheads to make those margins possible in any case.
But these are mere short-term matters. As to the long term, he says, one
must consider the Arab proverb often quoted by one of Shell's chief planners
in the 1970s: he who foretells the future lies, even when he is correct.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Royal Dutch Petroleum.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    NLZ  Netherlands, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P131  Crude Petroleum and Natural Gas.
    P138  Oil and Gas Field Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COMP  Company profile.
</TP>
