<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / (CORRECTED) Europe comes down to earth to look for common
ground - A new realism across the Continent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 5th January 1993) appended to this article.
'EUROPE is not a melting pot like the US', the Swiss professor said in
impeccable English at the office of a Californian multinational in
French-speaking Geneva. 'It is a salad - and we must learn to manage
diversity.'
But can the chefs in Brussels concoct a meal to satisfy the diverse palates
gathered at the feast?
In Switzerland, apparently not. Only days before Prof Stephane Garelli,
regional chief executive of Hewlett-Packard, spoke of the European salad,
Swiss voters had rejected entry into the European Economic Area - the
European Community's waiting room - despite his appeal for a Yes vote.
As commercial Europe opens its doors today for the first full day's business
in the single market, the big question is: will the Euro-diet prove too rich
for all its citizens' tastes?
A 12-day odyssey in unscientific pursuit of western European public opinion
confirmed that, in the very broadest terms, the EC and its amorphous goal of
'ever closer union' is still approved by a substantial majority - at least
on the continent of Europe.
A growing body of opinion says the pace being set by a remote EC leadership
is too fast and even, some say, too far. Germans speak of their fears for
the D-Mark. The French are openly concerned that Brus-sels is no longer
behaving like a fully owned subsidiary.
Yet from the deserted streets in Elsinore, Hamlet's Danish fortress of
Euro-doubt, through dithering Switzerland to the federalist heartlands of
Alsace and Baden-Wurttemberg down to Brussels-besotted Madrid and the
Anglo-Levantine bazaar of Gibraltar, one opinion was also shared: like it or
not, last month's Edinburgh summit has got the stalled European juggernaut
rolling again.
The new cement of European solidarity is worry that an overbearing
Eurocracy, daydreaming over expense account lunches, is unaware of the
recession being endured by taxpayers.
The Community's popularity was faltering long before Denmark's No and
France's much-derided petit oui in last summer's referendums. To Mr
Karlheinz Reif, head of the European Commission's opinion pollster,
Eurobarometer, changes in attitudes could be detected as far back as 1989,
even in such avowedly pro-EC countries as France and Italy.
A growing awareness of the imminent single market began to drag perceptions
of Europe down from the clouds. It would influence individual lives and,
hence, for the first time, became worthy of critical scrutiny.
Maastricht, Mr Reif says, brought something already lurking in the back of
the European psyche out into the open: 'Ordinary Europeans have stopped
seeing the EC as peace and security and have started looking at it more
closely.'
It is in the nature of views that the topography depends on the vantage
point of the spectator. Furthermore, few, if any, believe that they have any
chance of altering the landscape.
                        *      *      *
That sense of political impotence was tangible among Danes on the 17.44
stopping train from Elsinore to Copenhagen. With the ink on the Edinburgh
summit conclusions barely dry, Mr Poul Schluter, the prime minister, had
claimed with a politician's characteristic hyperbole 'a great day for
Denmark'.
Cradling a bouquet of treaty opt-outs, he warned his fellow citizens that
they must now choose between EC membership or leaving the Community. In one
carriage, however, his upbeat tone had fallen on cynical ears.
Sannah Jensen, a 24-year-old student, confessed many doubts but said she
would vote Yes again. Attributing anti-EC feeling largely to residual
anti-German nationalism from the 1864 war and the summer tide of tourists on
Denmark's beaches, she said: 'Every honest Dane says that now we have 11
countries that want to do something, we don't have a right to say you can't
do it.'
Yet only a few metres away, Brigitte, a nutrition student, fervently
disagreed. She pledged to vote No again to register her fury that her first
vote now appeared to have been arbitrarily invalidated. 'How many times are
we to vote? The government is trying to browbeat us with scare tactics - it
seems everything has been decided a long time ago.'
                        *      *      *
Similar fears of manipulation were shared, in altogether different
circumstances, some 700 miles away in Liechtenstein, the tiny principality
tucked up next to eastern Switzerland and linked to its neighbour by a
70-year-old customs union.
But was the Liechten-steiners' convincing vote to join the EEA a gesture of
independence from Berne after the Swiss's No vote a week previously? Or was
it a statement of dependence on the wider European market?
In a triumphant news conference, Prince Hans-Adam II praised his 30,000
subjects for following his persistent cable TV campaign to vote 'Yes to
Europe'. Yet both sides in Liechtenstein were united at least by agreeing
that their quest was not for Utopia but merely the least bad option.
                        *      *      *
It is a measure of the anxiety being generated by the combination of
recession and the European debate that Switzerland shuddered in self-doubt
after the referendum outcome in its tiny neighbour.
Much has been made of the schism in the Swiss poll on the EEA between the
German-speaking cantons' No and the French-speakers' Yes. Yet in the big
German-speaking cities, the Yes vote was also a majority. It was
conservative rural voters who bedecked their cars with appeals to 700 years
of neutrality and freedom.
With total Swiss unemployment up from 19,000 in August 1990 to 130,000
today, cold economic winds are playing their part in the debate, undermining
the nation's traditional view that it is safer out than in. 'Five years ago
we barely discussed EC membership,' one nationalist proclaimed. 'Now we
discuss nothing else.'
In urbane, metropolitan Geneva, the peasants' revolt is brushed aside by
executives at the US-based computer company Hewlett-Packard. Representing 35
nationalities and speaking a dozen languages, they earn in Swiss francs but
often enjoy the lower French cost of living across the border.
'The Swiss are naturally cautious,' said one. 'They have voted once. They
will vote again and again until they come round.'
                        *      *      *
Such sentiments are shared in the European Parliament in Strasbourg where
ideological differences nearly dissolve in the multi-partisan objective of a
deeper, wider Europe fit for Euro-politicians to play in. If absolute power
corrupts absolutely, then practically no power seems to do much the same.
On the day Mr John Major was greeted with boos and hisses and Mr Jacques
Delors declared 'time is on our side', it was hard not to conclude that
diversity of opinion is no more welcome in Europe's political capital than
it was in the Soviet Union.
In the words of Belgium's Mr Willy de Clercq, a one-time European
commissioner: 'We in the parliament believe Maastricht was too little, too
late.' And, indeed, that progress towards a united Europe was 'not fast
enough'.
But whose views do these people's representatives actually represent? In
more than 60 interviews across the continent, only one European voter argued
that the pace of union was too slow. Mr de Clercq now heads a committee
charged with explaining to the citizenry that 'those who want to stop in the
middle of the river are going to drown'.
But was that what Europeans really wanted? Mr de Clercq was dismissive. 'I
think it is more or less known what the European citizen wants', he said,
contradicting himself only minutes later when he agreed with Mr Delors'
statement that the Community was a good product that was proving hard to
sell.
                        *      *      *
What, in that case, can be sold to humble mortals on terra firma? At the
Mercedes-Benz plant in Stuttgart or the Citroen repair shop in Lyons, few
use such esoteric Euro-terminology as Mr Delors' 'variable geometry' to
describe their plans for the future.
From cities where memories of the second world war are still vivid, most
workers remain loyal to Monnet's and Schuman's vision of European unity. But
it is the recession, immigration and jobs - and Brussels' apparent
powerlessness to address these issues - that are canteen talk in the German
plant, now on an extended Christmas lay-off, and worry the redundancy-riven
workshop in Lyons.
Of the MEPs interviewed in Strasbourg, it was Mr Bruno Gollnisch of France's
widely despised, extreme-right National Front, who seemed to be addressing
many of these 'live', if unfashionable issues. But his nationalist solutions
appeared to have surprisingly little resonance in Stuttgart.
Only the Ossis - the former citizens of East Germany - proved decidedly
illiberal compared with their western compatriots. One of these, Steffen, a
maintenance worker, insisted the Community was 'all right as it is, and
should remain so', but he firmly rejected a single currency and demanded
immigration controls.
His colleagues from further east differed only over who should be allowed
in. 'We could come in more or less straight away,' said a Hungarian, 'and
maybe the Czech lands . . . but the rest should stay out.'
In Mr Gollnisch's home territory of Lyons, the most overt racism among
diners at Les Six Troyens restaurant appeared to be against the
foot-dragging British. But among the younger French clientele, a
'Maastricht, Non' psychology is growing.
'European unification means one government,' said a bearded travelling
salesman. 'That was Yugoslavia before, and look at it today. . . '
                        *      *      *
Only in Madrid was it possible to encounter levels of European rapture
capable of registering on the de Clercq scale. At the Fundacion March, a
group of post-graduate political scientists groped to explain why Spanish
public opinion was so universally uncritical towards the Community and its
works.
'It is a choice between Africa and Europe,' said one cynic with a sheepish
grin. Another more reflectively proposed: 'Only people - like the British
and Danes - who think the government of the Community is less responsible
than their own can afford the luxury of questioning it.'
                        *      *      *
Back in Switzerland, Prof Garelli, former director of the World Business
Forum at Davos, contends that the Single European Act was the catalyst for a
single market modelled on the business agenda for the so-called 'Bankers'
Europe' so detested by left and hard right alike. It was now the duty of the
politicians, he said, to make their programme relevant to popular demands.
A cursory rummage though continental public opinion suggests that the
Maastricht equation needs retuning if it is to achieve that end. If not,
there is a danger of creating a divided Community: a middle-class adventure
playground, full of opportunities for the multilingual executive with any
eye to the main chance, but for the less privileged, a bleaker place, prone
to destructive extremism.
Away from politics, however, it is not all bad news. Inch by inch, month by
month, human European bonds are strengthening. The transport network grows
yearly more remarkable, the frontiers less notice able.
British pub bores can now drone on about the roadworks on the Autoroutes,
but they do so over warm beer.
The Spanish still guard their eccentric working hours and the Greeks their
cheap cigarettes and affluent German tourists.
As yet, the bratwurst in a croissant has still to be invented.
CORRECTION
Professor Stephane Garelli, a consultant to Hewlett-Packard, was incorrectly
described yesterday as the company's regional chief executive. That position
is held by Mr Franco Mariotti.
