<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Plan for Bosnia stirs disputes: The Moslems object to
suggested boundaries but at least all sides are prepared to discuss the
EC-UN proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE peace plan for Bosnia-Hercegovina has the merit of having been accepted
for the first time as a basis for negotiation by all the warring parties.
However, many of its detailed provisions are still hotly disputed.
At the heart of the disagreements about the plan - tabled in Geneva at the
weekend by the two co-chairmen of the international conference on the former
Yugoslavia, Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen - lie Bosnian Moslem objections to
some of the boundaries of the proposed 10 essentially autonomous provinces
making up the new decentralised state, in which Serbian Moslems would
control nearly 50 per cent of the territory of the former Yugoslav republic
of Bosnia-Hercegovina.
What Mr Vance, the United Nations' special representative, and Lord Owen,
representing the European Community, have proposed is a constitution which
would recognise the three big ethnic groups - Moslems, Serbs and Croats - as
the constituent units of the new state, as well as a group of 'others'.
In spite of all their avowed efforts to eschew a purely ethnic division of
the country by taking other relevant factors - such as history, geography,
the economic situation and communications - fully into account, they have,
in the end, had to draw the provincial boundaries largely on the basis of
ethnic criteria.
Thus, each of the main ethnic groups will be dominant in three provinces,
with Sarajevo remaining a 'mixed' province. That will allow the Serbs to
retain extensive, but by no means all, areas they have 'ethnically
cleansed'. Though the Serbs have demanded a corridor linking two of their
assigned provinces, they feel they can do a territorial deal with the
Croats.
That is very different from the attitude of the Bosnian Moslems, who not
only feel they are being deprived of territory they consider their
birthright, but who fear that the Serb and Croat provinces will some day
organise referendums on whether to merge with their parent states, Serbia
and Croatia.
The central government, as well as all the new provinces, except the 'mixed'
province of Sarajevo, would have separate democratically elected
legislatures, democratically chosen chief executives and independent
judiciaries. The nine-member presidency of the new state would be composed
of three representatives each of the three main constituent ethnic groups.
The three main ethnic groups would also be equally represented in the
provincial government of Sarajevo, while the capital itself would become an
'open city', which should be demilitarised at the earliest possible date.
The state of Bosnia-Hercegovina should also be progressively demilitarised
under UN-EC supervision.
In keeping with the principle of freedom of movement throughout the new
state, laid down in the draft constitution, the co-chairmen have proposed
'throughways' between provinces, policed by UN or other international
forces, to ensure that the free flow of traffic is not obstructed and that
military forces or material do not move through these crossings.
Special 'blue routes' guaranteeing safe passage to humanitarian aid and
civilians to and from Sarajevo, which, after the cessation of hostilities,
would be extended to cover the whole country until normal freedom of
movement is established, have also been proposed.
The separation of the armed forces in Bosnia-Hercegovina would have to be
negotiated in the light of provincial boundaries and the co-chairmen have
proposed the areas to which the various forces should withdraw. It is
envisaged that there will be no military forces in Sarajevo province.
Once the new constitution is agreed and there is a return to normal civil
life, elections supervised by the UN and the EC would take place. But Lord
Owen said this was unlikely to happen for 'a considerable number of months'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
