<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / How the new Bosnia would look
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Under the proposals tabled in Geneva at the weekend by Mr Cyrus Vance and
Lord Owen, Bosnia-Hercegovina would become a decentralised state of 10
largely autonomous provinces.
It is proposed that the three main ethnic groups in Bosnia-Hercegovina -
Moslems, Serbs and Croats - should each be allocated three provinces in
which they will have a large majority. Sarajevo province would remain a
mixed community and Sarajevo should become a demilitarised 'open city'.
Under the proposals, the provinces marked with the numbers 1, 5 and 9 would
have a predominantly Moslem population; 2, 4 and 6 would be peopled largely
by Serbs, with a Moslem minority in 4; and 3, 8 and 10 would have a majority
of Croats, with a strong minority of Moslems, particularly in 10.
</TEXT>
