<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Arms treaty is a hostage to fortune - Potential dangers for
Start 2
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
START 2 is, as Presidents George Bush and Boris Yeltsin stressed yesterday,
uniquely radical among arms treaties: it has sharply reduced armaments
rather than, as Mr Bush said, simply 'freezing the arms race in place'.
Its radicalism, and the speed with which it was signed ('a matter of a few
months', said Mr Yeltsin proudly yesterday, contrasting it with 15 years for
the first Start treaty) means that it faces three large potential dangers,
which there has been no time to defuse.
First, such large cuts will take time: all of 10 years, to 2003, for the two
countries to bring down their strategic weaponry to the 3,000-3,500 warheads
permitted (plus a maximum of 1,750 submarine-launched warheads). In that
period, relations between the two states could worsen - will worsen, if the
feared lurch to Russian authoritarianism happens.
This could mean a breaching of the treaties, a freezing of the missiles'
destruction (the more so since this is agreed to be done with US assistance)
and a return to arms build-up.
Second, the opposition to the treaties within the Russian parliament is
strong - though Mr Yeltsin confidently declared yesterday that it was 'not
the majority', being confined to those who 'are against everything positive
which occurs in Russia'.
Opponents have already latched on to what they say are unequal aspects in
the treaty, claiming that the provisions for inspection give US officials
carte blanche on Russian territory. The claim forced Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the
foreign minister, to tell parliament on December 10 that the arrangements
were predicated on Russia receiving Dollars 400m (Pounds 263.1m) to assist
the dismantling of the weapons and that they 'freed our citizens from an
additional burden of defence spending'.
However, the opposition deputies share, and seek to stimulate, a feeling of
shame in Russia that it is reduced to inequality by comparison with its
historic enemy, the US. Mr Iona Andronov, deputy chairman of the
parliament's international relations committee, said last month 'this
agreement. . . has brought a great nation to its knees'. Mr Yeltsin,
however, has made a point of involving Mr Yevgenny Ambartsumov, chairman of
the international relations committee, in the talks: Mr Ambartsumov, a
one-time radical who now takes a moderately nationalist position, will give
vital support in parliament.
Third, there remains the Ukrainian problem. Ukraine, Belarus and Kazakhstan
retain strategic nuclear arms (they have sent their more numerous tactical
weapons to Russia). All three states have twice mutually promised to
renounce nuclear weapons: once in Alma Ata in December 1991 and again in
Lisbon last May. All have committed themselves to ratifying Start and to
signing the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT).
Only Kazakhstan, so far, has ratified Start. Ukraine, as the largest of the
non-Russian nuclear powers, is demonstrating what Mr Bohdan Kravchenko, an
adviser to the country's government, recently admitted was an 'ambivalent'
position. It has insisted on exercising sovereignty over all the 176 nuclear
missiles deployed on its territory (saying it was ensuring their 'non-use');
it is now seeking security guarantees in return for the pledge to destroy
warheads - a pledge which has anyway shifted from being executed by 1994 to
the end of this decade.
In a recent article in the Wall Street Journal, Mr Zalmay Khalilzad, former
US assistant deputy under-secretary of defence, claimed that 'the mood in
Kiev is shifting against disarmament' and forecast that the parliamentary
debate on Start and NPT scheduled for next month 'is. . . likely to demand
their renegotiation'. Were this to be Ukraine's position, it is likely that
neighbouring Belarus, at least, would follow suit.
After the triumphs of Moscow yesterday, Ukraine becomes the focus of
diplomatic efforts to address its fears about non-nuclear life next to a
nuclear Russia.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
WHERE HAVE ALL THE WARHEADS GONE?
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Deployed strategic nuclear warheads
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
US: 9,862 warheads, being: 500 warheads on MX/Peacekeeper ICBMs; 1,500
warheads on Minuteman III ICBMs; 370 warheads on Minuteman II ICBMs;
2,816 warheads on Trident I (C-4) SLBMs; 768 warheads on Trident II
(D-5) SLBMs; 1,520 warheads on B-1B bombers; 1,860 warheads on B-52H
bombers; 528 warheads on B-52G bombers.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Former Soviet Union: 10,909 warheads, being: 296 warheads on SS-11
ICBMs; 40 warheads on SS-13 ICBMs; 176 warheads on SS-17 ICBMs; 3,080
warheads on SS-18 ICBMs; 1,800 warheads on SS-19 ICBMs; 920 warheads on
SS-24 ICBMs; 315 warheads on SS-25 ICBMs; 176 warheads on SS-N-6 SLBMs;
280 warheads on SS-N-8 SLBMs; 672 warheads on SS-N-18 SLBMs; 1,200
warheads on SS-N-20 SLBMs; 448 warheads on SS-N-23 SLBMs; 240 warheads
on Bear-G bombers; 1,074 warheads on Bear-H bombers; 192 warheads on
Blackjack bombers.
of which:
Belarus: 81 warheads on SS-25 ICBMs.
Kazakhstan: 1,410 warheads, being: 1,040 warheads on SS-18 ICBMs; and
370 warheads on Bear-H bombers.
Ukraine: 1,656 warheads, being: 460 warheads on SS-24 ICBMs; 780
warheads on SS-19 ICBMs; 224 warheads on Bear-H bombers; and 192
warheads on Blackjack bombers.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
China: up to 320 warheads, being: 68 warheads on ICBMs; an estimated 12
warheads on SLBMs; and up to 240 warheads on H-6 bombers.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
France: 402 warheads, being: 384 warheads on M-4 SLBMs; and 18 warheads
on SSBS S-3D intermediate range missiles.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
UK: 192 warheads on Polaris A-3 TK SLBMs; and up to 512 warheads under
the Trident programme.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
START 2 at a glance:
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Implementation will be achieved in two stages up to the year 2003,
interim ceilings to be reached in the first seven years after the treaty
enters into force.
 -By January 1, 2003, total number of strategic nuclear warheads held by
  each side to have been reduced to 3,000-3,500 units. This means the
  elimination of 15,000 of the two sides' current combined arsenals of
  21,000 warheads.
 -Land-based intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs) with multiple
  warheads to be eliminated.
 -Each side to cut the number of warheads on submarine-launched
  ballistic missiles (SLBMs) to a level of 1,700-1,750 units.
 -Limits to be imposed on number of warheads with which heavy bombers
  on each side can be equipped, varying from 750 to 1,250 units of any
  type.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: The International Institute of Strategic Studies, The Arms
Control Association
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
