<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / VAT spreads as central Europe reforms taxes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON, VINCENT BOLAND, CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI and NICHOLAS
DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRAGUE, WARSAW, BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CENTRAL Europe's determined effort to prepare for full membership of the
European Community by the turn of the century moved a step further at the
weekend as the new Czech Republic and Slovakia combined the achievement of
separate statehood with introduction of value added tax.
Harmonisation of tax systems among EC members was one requirement for
creating the European single market, whose present boundaries do not extend
beyond the eastern borders of Germany. But tax reform has posed special
problems for the former communist countries of east and central Europe which
had neither graduated personal income taxes, nor corporation taxes, nor
VAT-type consumption taxes.
Over the last two years task forces of western tax experts have been working
in central Europe under the auspices of the Centre for Co-operation with
European Economies in Transition, the main conduit for technical assistance
to the former communist states set up by the Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development, the Paris-based economic think-tank.
Hungary has been the pace-setter in tax as in other key institutional
reforms, having introduced VAT and other tax reforms gradually over the last
few years. On January 1 the government introduced a modified three-tier VAT
system with zero rating only for drugs and household electricity, 6 per cent
on foodstuffs and a top 25 per cent rate on most other items.
The Czech and Slovak rates are 5 per cent for services and a few essential
items and 23 per cent on other goods. Poland is due to introduce VAT on July
1 and has decided on a zero rating for a restricted list of essential items,
7 per cent on some food and other items and a top rate of 22 per cent.
The collapse of the communist system and the drive to privatise the economy
and introduce market principles has simultaneously reduced tax revenues, due
to the collapse of many state industries, and raised demands for higher
spending, especially in new areas such as unemployment and retraining. The
result has been soaring budget deficits which made it difficult to conform
with International Monetary Fund-imposed performance criteria linked to IMF
loan agreements.
The introduction of VAT and other taxes is designed to widen the tax revenue
base and adequately tax higher incomes resulting from the emergence of new
players in the rapidly growing private sector.
More controversially, VAT revenue is also designed to offset the cost of tax
concessions designed to attract foreign investment.
As the recent IMF agreement with Poland shows, the Fund has recently
increased its temporary tolerance of high budget deficits pending the
introduction of VAT and other reforms. These are intended to ensure that the
new democratic states generate the revenues required to balance budgets over
a longer period and finance the social safety net needed to keep
unemployment associated with the transition to a market economy politically
manageable.
Poland is expected to cut its budget deficit from nearly 8 per cent last
year to around 5.5 per cent this year while the Hungarian budget plans to
reduce the deficit to 5.9 per cent from 7.5 per cent in 1992. In all cases,
however, higher VAT and other taxes are expected to boost inflation by at
least 5 per cent this year against the background of what promises to be
higher real incomes and export-led increases in output after three years of
steep recession.
</TEXT>
