<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Leaders bathe in historic praise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALMOST no one who was not paid to do so greeted or celebrated Start 2 in
Moscow yesterday: at 21 degrees below, it was not the weather for it and,
after a year of economic reform, there was not the stomach for it.
A couple of Russian children waving the Stars and Stripes had stood outside
Spaso House, the US ambassador's residence, when President George Bush's
party arrived on Saturday: Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky, who keeps the banner of
fascist imperialism flying whenever he can, had earlier led 10 supporters to
picket the airport with signs saying: 'Hands off Iraq.'
Otherwise, Muscovites went about their holiday business: queueing for
petrol, looking for food and telling foreign television crews that they
didn't give two kopeks (0.5 cents at the current exchange rate) about what
was happening in the Kremlin.
In that chill fortress, Mr Bush looked weary as he commended the 'most
significant arms agreement ever' at the Saturday night banquet in the Hall
of Facets: Mr Boris Yeltsin, bouncy and at his most amiable, called the
agreement a 'Christmas present to the world', a phrase which Mr Bush's
speechwriters either could not match or thought too sugary for inclusion.
They were bested again yesterday, when Mr Yeltsin's scribes pulled an
'agreement of hope' out of the phrase bag, it sounding even more soothing in
Russian.
Sitting in St Vladimir's Hall before their officials and the press, the two
men assured each other of their historic importance: Mr Bush remembered that
Mr Yeltsin had saved democracy in August 1991 by climbing on top of a tank,
and Mr Yeltsin said that 'my friend George' possessed 'political and
personal qualities (which) had helped to make the change from the cold war
to warm relations between our countries'.
</TEXT>
