<PROFILE>_AN-DADBPAEGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / UN struggles for a role in Somalia: An inauspicious start to
today's peace talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE humiliation of Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, United Nations secretary
general, by 500 anti-UN protesters in Mogadishu yesterday was a
demonstration of the difficulties facing the UN chief in critical Somali
peace talks which open in the Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa today.
Demonstrators loyal to Gen Mohamed Farrar Aideed, Somalia's most powerful
warlord, chanted 'Boutros Ghali go home' as they pelted the UN headquarters
in Mogadishu with rocks and grapefruit skins and tore down and stamped on UN
flags and signboards. The UN chief was forced to abandon plans to visit the
building and retreated to the airport by helicopter, leaving some of his
most senior aides besieged inside the headquarters.
It was an inauspicious start to the secretary-general's Somalia peace
mission. Fourteen Somali factions are due to meet in Addis Ababa this
morning under Mr Boutros Ghali's chairmanship in the first serious
round-table political conference aimed at beginning a process to end the
bitter clan warfare that has destroyed Somalia and created a famine which
has cost at least 300,000 lives.
Finding a political solution to Somalia's two-year conflict is fundamental
to ending the faction fighting and therefore the starvation created largely
by banditry. Without political reconciliation the cycle of violence and
death from starvation cannot be broken.
But for the UN the stakes are high. Its repeated efforts in the past 24
months to broker peace talks have failed, and many believe today's talks
have come about only because of the US military intervention in Somalia.
Several of the faction leaders invited to the informal talks are deeply
critical of the role the UN has played in Somalia. Some go as far as
accusing the UN of fuelling the fighting by exacerbating divisions among the
factions.
At best, UN officials are hoping to lay the groundwork for an agenda, venue
and list of delegates to a national reconciliation conference, probably in
Somalia within three months, which will pave the way for an interim assembly
and administration. At worst, the conference could collapse in acrimony with
the warlords accusing the UN of malicious meddling.
Failure in Addis Ababa could sink hopes for political reconciliation and
discredit the UN and Mr Boutros Ghali, already under pressure in Bosnia and
Cambodia.
Critics say the UN may have already sown the seeds of failure by convening a
conference without adequately preparing the groundwork. They also say that
by inviting only warlords and factions, and not intellectuals and elders,
the UN is legitimising those directly responsible for the violence and
famine who do not have popular support and cannot deliver genuine
reconciliation.
'All the conditions for failure are there,' says Mr Abdul Mohamed, a member
of the conference secretariat and a Horn of Africa expert. 'The UN has not
done its political homework in Somalia and this is going to haunt them and
further marginalise the UN at a time when it is critical for it to regain
the confidence of Somalis.'
Before any real work can be done resolving the differences between the
splintered clan-based factions, the UN must try to win over Gen Aideed, who
controls most of Mogadishu, and his ally in the Somalia National Alliance
(SNA), Col Omar Jess, who controls the southern port of Kismayu. It was here
that a British UN relief worker was shot dead on Saturday, prompting Unicef
to withdraw its international staff from the city yesterday.
Both men are hostile to the UN. They want to deal solely with the US and are
intent on exploiting divisions between the US and the UN over disarmament of
factions and the timetable for the handover from US forces in Somalia to UN
peacekeepers.
In a statement before leaving Mogadishu for Addis Ababa, Gen Aideed said
that the 'UN bureaucrats had failed time and time again to demonstrate any
understanding of the intricate political situation in Somalia'. He said he
agreed to take part in the conference only because it was 'informal and
preparatory'. He went on to attack the UN role in Somalia as 'too ad hoc,
meddling, secretive, divisive and partial' to produce any positive results
for the good of the country.
His blunt criticism of the UN intensified doubts about the chances of
success at the Addis Ababa conference.
In private, senior US officials also voice criticism about the UN role in
Somalia and say it was the organisation's failure to resolve the crisis and
mount a serious humanitarian relief operation which prompted US military
intervention. US officials also say they have had greater success in
political reconciliation than the UN, brokering the first face-to-face talks
between Gen Aideed and his arch rival, Mr Ali Mahdi Mohamed, last month.
Washington, however, is reluctant to get drawn in too far. Mr Bush has
continued to insist that US troops are on a limited humanitarian mission and
must pull out within weeks and hand over to UN peacekeepers.
Mr Boutros Ghali has tried unsuccessfully to put pressure on the US to
disarm the factions and is believed to be stalling on talks about the
transition from the US-led operation to a UN force until Washington gives in
to his request. He does not want to inherit the problems of disarmament.
For better or for worse the UN is going to be the key player in Somalia. The
challenge in Addis Ababa today will be to impress that reality on the
faction leaders and start building the framework for a broad-based national
political reconciliation.
Editorial Comment, Page 27
</TEXT>
