FT  04 JAN 93 / Israeli agent dies in stabbing: Palestinian shot dead in
Gaza
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN ISRAELI secret service officer was stabbed to death in Jerusalem
yesterday and a Palestinian shot dead in the Gaza Strip as tensions
persisted over deportation to Lebanon last month of 415 Palestinians accused
of being Moslem militants from the occupied territories.
Police said Mr Chaim Nachmani, a 25-year-old man stabbed and bludgeoned to
death at an apartment in a wealthy inner suburb of Jerusalem, was an officer
of the General Security Service, or Shin Bet, who was involved in an
operation at the time. It said his killer, apparently an Arab, was known to
the authorities, but gave no further details.
Mr Nachmani was the first member of the security forces to be killed since
Israeli carried out the controversial deportations on December 17. It was
understood to be the first killing for 10 years of an officer of the Shin
Bet. The service is responsible for much of the intelligence and undercover
work carried out by Israeli forces in the occupied territories and is feared
and hated by most Palestinians.
Earlier in the Gaza Strip, an 18-year-old Palestinian was shot dead and 11
others were wounded in clashes with Israeli troops following the lifting of
a four-day curfew on the heavily populated territory.
Yesterday, Mr Yossi Beilin, deputy foreign minister, flew to Cairo to
discuss the deportations, which threaten Middle East peace talks. Later Mr
Amr Moussa, Egyptian foreign minister, said it would be 'really helpful to
the peace process' if Israel would heed UN security council resolution 799
and reverse the deportations.
But Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin told students before news of yesterday's
killings the move had curbed Gaza and West Bank violence: 'It served as a
real blow to the Islamic fundamentalist terror groups.' Israeli police fired
rubber bullets and tear gas at thousands of ultra-orthodox Jews
demonstrating in Jerusalem against the uncovering during building work of
ancient graves.
