<DOCNO>FT931-16871</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DADBPAD2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Life in the Single Market: Global shopper takes a step out
from the shadows - Consumer convergence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SALAMA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HARVARD professor Ted Levitt electrified the marketing community in the
early 1970s with his belief in the existence of a global consumer.
According to Levitt, technology was driving markets in such a way as to make
'different cultural preferences, national tastes and standards vestiges of
the past'.
But it was not until the late 1980s, when plans for the single market were
launched and acted as a catalyst for new thinking, that the degree of
consumer convergence across countries became a live issue for the mass of
companies.
Today it is commonplace to hear companies as diverse as Shell and Suchard
justifying their strategies in terms of common consumer trends, the
internationalisation of the media and the growing irrelevance of national
boundaries.
But to what extent are these beliefs valid? And what are the implications
for companies?
There is no doubt that there are powerful common trends operating across
Europe.
For example, all the major European countries are experiencing a significant
decline in their youth population. This will affect both the personnel
policy of all companies as well as the strategies of individual companies,
such as Heineken and Nike which have traditionally relied heavily on this
group for their sales.
Equally, the incomes of Europeans in work continue to increase - albeit at a
different pace, but with the same kind of consequences. It is helping to
raise consumer expectations, lessening deference towards companies and
reducing the willingness to accept inferior products and services.
At a sector level, common needs can also be seen to be emerging.
The growing inability of all governments to finance welfare state systems is
raising fears among consumers, especially older ones, about their ability to
fund their retirement. Some governments, such as in Italy, have reacted by
raising the retirement age and tightening eligibility criteria, rather than
by privatising pension provision in the way that the UK has done. Yet there
is some common ground in pension and saving product opportunities across
Europe.
But in spite of a background of increasing uniformity, the evidence of
continued differences across Europe is overwhelming. In each case, these
differences can be traced back to variations in factors such as legislation,
government policy, corporate marketing strategies, retail environments and
product availability.
Two examples are:
A higher proportion of people in Germany and the Netherlands place the
environment at the top of their list of concerns and there is no reason to
suppose this situation will change. Legislation which applies to packaging
in Germany, together with the pro-active policies of national retailers,
have been critical in shaping consumer attitudes and are unlikely to be
copied with anything like the same force in other countries. Throughout
Europe, higher levels of education, reduced deference towards the medical
establishment and the desire of governments to contain health spending have
combined to provide a boost to over-the-counter drugs sales. But the
tendency for consumers to consult their doctor or pharmacist for an ailment
such as a cough varies considerably. Again, continued differences in payment
systems and in the relationship between doctors and pharmacists will
perpetuate this situation.
It is to be expected that some of the differences between countries will be
eroded by some powerful forces. In particular, the consumer's desire to be
different and to experience new things cannot be underestimated. For each
Englishman who starts eating croissants for breakfast and drinking wine,
there is a Frenchman who is taking up cereals in the morning and drinking
beer with his evening meal.
To this extent, cross-country European niches will develop.
At the same time, companies are playing a key role in stimulating
convergence. The growth of international brands such as McDonald's, Ikea,
Nike and Toys R Us and the increased co-ordination of company marketing
policy - think of the way in which Unilever has rolled out brands such as
Radion across Europe - are raising the number of common experiences. These
factors could prove the most important in promoting convergence.
Others are not quite as important as they might at first appear. After all,
when taking into account factors such as holiday taking, it must be
recognised that for most Europeans this is still a domestic phenomenon.
The relaxation of protectionist legislation has not significantly changed
behaviour. Germany's removal of beer purity laws did not lead to an
avalanche of imported beers.
European niches are emerging but national and regional differences still
need to be considered. Co-ordinating activities while being sensitive to
local market conditions is a difficult task - and one at which few companies
have excelled.
Eric Salama is joint managing director of the Henley Centre, the business
consultancy.
</TEXT>
