<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Life in the Single Market: Knowing when to drop the fat
operatic soprano - Carmakers' strategies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOLKSWAGEN may be preparing a VW Golf Europa special edition to celebrate
the single market, but the company remains adamant that it will continue
specific strategies market by market.
According to Mr Philip Holliday, account manager for VW at the carmaker's UK
advertising agency BMP DDB Needham, the group follows a common overall
advertising strategy for Europe. This is built around the perceived virtues
of reliability and quality but the interpretation of these features is left
to national markets.
'German television ads tend to be rather literal, they assert something and
give a very factual demonstration of reliability. In the UK it is much less
direct. We show reliability as an emotional quality. In the face of
adversity the car is there as a consistent, reliable friend.'
In the UK the angry girlfriend may throw away her diamonds and her fur coat,
but never the keys to her VW Golf.
Mr Holliday insists that many advertising approaches do not translate to
another country because of the humour or the dialogue.
Fiat presented its Tipo small family car in the UK with a television
campaign including an overweight operatic soprano appearing through the sun
roof, but the approach has to be rather different in Italy.
On the other hand some Volkswagen markets elsewhere in Europe did pick up
the British VW Golf advert, in which the only squeak was in the lady
driver's earring. Filmed in Spain the only dialogue was a few words and
grunts spoken in Italian.
Strategies towards the consumer also depend crucially on the relative
strength of the individual car brand in a particular market.
Gradually shares of individual markets are being evened out, but the
carmakers' fortunes still vary widely. The Fiat group has a share of 12 per
cent across Europe, but in Italy it takes 44 per cent of all new car sales
and only 2 per cent in the UK.
This relative market strength crucially affects pricing policies, and goes
some way to explaining often widely divergent new car prices across Europe.
Car prices will continue to differ from market to market driven not least by
currency fluctuations and different tax regimes. But there is growing
evidence that they will tend to converge as the borders between national
markets become less distinct, and market shares become more equal.
Mr Louis Schweitzer, chairman and chief executive of Renault, says: 'At the
moment where you have a bigger market share and more loyalty, you can charge
more, but these opportunities will become more limited. Prices are
converging in different markets and carmakers will have less flexibility in
marketing techniques.'
</TEXT>
