<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Life in the Single Market: The Polish dealer feeding the EC
market - Chris Bobinski meets a businessman whose gaze stretches from the
Atlantic to the Urals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE revolution which swept communism out of eastern Europe helped make Jan
Kulczyk rich. The single market is likely to make him richer.
This 42-year-old Polish millionaire, clad soberly in grey slacks and a blue
blazer, has moved with apparent ease from the old world of communist rule to
the new one where capitalism holds sway - and where the whole of Europe now
appears a place to make money.
Controlling 36 companies with sales approaching 3,000bn zloty (Pounds 124m),
Mr Kulczyk's interests include banking, Volkswagen vehicle distribution in
Poland and, above all, agribusiness. A mild-mannered cosmopolitan - he pays
taxes in Germany and has homes in Berlin, Lugano, Poznan and Warsaw - he
uses his spare cash to sponsor classical music festivals.
Mr Kulczyk made his fortune selling fruit, vegetables and meat to the EC.
Now, in addition, he buys western food processing machinery to sell in the
east. He says the single market will act as a powerful spur to this form of
two-way trade with the Community - a process which should eventually benefit
east and west.
Frontier-free trading will give Poland particular benefits by easing access
to western technology, he believes. But some of his preoccupations are more
mundane.
Musing on the new opportunities for cross-border trading of livestock as a
result of the ending of EC customs controls, he enthuses: 'I will no longer
have to send sheep specifically to one country.'
Prospects for increased EC commerce depend crucially on improving transport
links. Mr Kulczyk and other businessmen want to build a 270km toll motorway
linking Berlin to his native Poznan and beyond. A feasibility study on the
project is to be ready next month and Mr Kulczyk says western road building
consortia have promised Dollars 800m (Pounds 526.3m) of credits once the
plan gets the green light from the authorities.
A further landmark in 1993 is another sign of Poland's changing business
times. He is on the board of the state owned bank, Wielkopolski Bank
Kredytowy, which is to be privatised in 1993. The bank, like the PZU state
insurance company, is a shareholder in the motorway development company.
Mr Kulczyk, whose corporate career started in 1975, believes Polish
businessmen will link the new capitalist markets in the east and the
extended free trade area of the west. Business associates say the gift of
getting quickly to the point is just one of his talents. 'He combines a
romantic Slav nature with Germanic ability to organise,' says one admiring
colleague.
His family business, started by his father in 1956, has had plenty of
practice at building economic bridges. Mr Kulczyk senior set up a West
Berlin-based food trading company which entered co-operation with several
Polish state agricultural exporters. Some of these have now been privatised
 -and are now controlled by Mr Kulczyk.
The original Berlin company has now been transformed into Kulczyk
Aussenhandel, importing food processing plant into Poland and the former
Soviet republics.
In another example of his activities, Mr Kulczyk has teamed up with Krupp to
help build near Poznan a Dollars 100m 150,000 tonnes per year processing
plant, a venture which will increase Poland's rapeseed processing capacity
by a quarter.
Such deals have brought Mr Kulczyk profits - and a distaste for publicity.
'Too much exposure at home tends to bring trouble,' he says.
As for the future, Mr Kulczyk says Poland should live in 'symbiosis' with
its more highly industrialised neighbours to the west.
'Workers in the European Community shouldn't feel that low wage employees in
Poland are a threat to their jobs,' he declares, displaying what appears to
be somewhat exaggerated belief in EC workers' espousal of the vision of
international capitalism.
'Rather, this offers a chance to expand their companies' business.'
Mr Kulczyk's European horizons stretch east as well as west. Last year he
helped set up Euro Agro Centrum, a company which aims to sell food
processing equipment from western Europe to countries like Ukraine.
'There, the possibilities are boundless,' he says. Mr Kulczyk clearly
believes the single market has a lot further to go; and the direction will
be predominantly eastwards. 'Ukraine,' he adds, 'is the future.'
Poland, Mr Kulczyk says, should make the best of its natural advantages,
here and now, and that does not mean high tech products but simpler things -
such as roads for transit traffic and food production.
</TEXT>
