<DOCNO>FT931-16880</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DADBPADTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Life in the Single Market: Masters of cut and thrust - The
Four Marketeers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH and ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ARCHITECT
IT WAS a job well done, even if his part in it finished before he would have
liked.
'Broadly speaking, it's been completed in time,' intones Lord Cockfield, the
man who, as a European Commissioner, was responsible for shaping plans for
the single market between 1984 and 1988.
He would have loved to have stayed on in Brussels but was withdrawn four
years ago when Margaret Thatcher decided he had 'gone native'.
With the air of a stern Dickensian parson, the 76-year-old Cockfield says
the 5 per cent of his single market recommendations not implemented are
'minor compared with the vast panorama of the programme'.
But the now part-time accountancy adviser still betrays more than a whiff of
acrimony towards the Tory government. 'It had very little understanding of
what the single market meant,' he sniffs. 'It was thinking of areas like
transport - it never thought it had to take fiscal matters into account as
well.'
He is predictably dismissive of the UK's efforts to bring the European
central bank to London and is a believer in a single European currency but
does not think it will be the Ecu. His money is on the D-Mark.
HIS SUCCESSOR
Italy, bottom of the EC league for transferring single market legislation
into its national law, had been piqued into rapid action just ahead of the
January 1 deadline.
In an 11th-hour effort, the Italian parliament authorised a fast-track
procedure for implementing 33 directives covering everything from the
labelling of medicines to the trade in fresh meat.
The move should spare the blushes of Italy's new commissioner, Mr Raniero
Vanni d'Archirafi, when he arrives in Brussels on Wednesday. For at least
the next two years he will be responsible for making the internal market
work.
The appointment raised a few eyebrows within the Commission when it was
announced a fortnight ago, given Italy's poor track record on
implementation.
GONE FISHING
Come New Year's Eve, most of the Brussels architects of the single market
appeared to have folded up their blueprints and disappeared instead of
sticking around for the launch of their masterplan. The headquarters of the
European Commission was almost deserted as officials, true to form, took the
week between Christmas and New Year off.
PRIVATE FUNCTION
Mr Jacques Delors, the Commission president, was said to have celebrated
privately somewhere in France. His spokesman said a public display of
enthusiasm would have been inappropriate given the economic and political
background. In any case, he added, Mr Delors had always made it clear that
establishment of the single market would not be 'un big bang' but a gradual
process.
MIND GAMES
Contacted on New Year's Eve, advisers to Mr Martin Bangemann, the internal
market commissioner, were unable to say where he intended to celebrate the
New Year.
'He keeps changing his mind,' said one.
THOSE AGAINST
One group unlikely to be celebrating arrival of the single market is the
anti-federalist Campaign for an Independent Britain. Its Christmas card, in
stark red and white, featured an accusatory Kitchener-like Santa Claus on
the cover posing the question: 'Will 1992 be your LAST British Christmas
before European Union?'
'Britain's future is in OUR hands this Christmas', it reads inside, urging
recipients to help the campaign to oppose the Maastricht treaty.
</TEXT>
