<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Life in the Single Market: A question of carts and horses -
Monetary union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WILL the existence of separate national currencies undermine Europe's single
market? And what will happen to the ideal of a level European playing field
if a group of EC member countries decide to form a monetary union?
In principle there is no reason why a single market or customs union, with
no barriers to internal trade, should need a single currency, or somehow be
'incomplete' without one. There has been no suggestion the recently
negotiated North American Free Trade Agreement would require a single North
American currency. Instead, a monetary union implies a trade-off between the
gains from no exchange risk or transactions costs and the costs from losing
the flexibility to change currency and interest rates.
Separate currencies in the single market mean a degree of uncertainty and
transactions costs. Inefficiencies caused by short-term fluctuations in
exchange rates are likely to be small and largely avoidable for businesses.
The Commission estimates that elimination of foreign exchange transaction
costs would add about 0.5 per cent to the Community's GDP.
More serious is the risk that sudden speculative attacks on currencies,
unrelated to underlying economic realities, will unfairly reward or penalise
companies in different countries. But the UK had a much higher inflow of
Japanese direct investment in the late 1980s than any other European
country, even though sterling was not a member of the European exchange rate
mechanism.
But single currencies have costs too. If all countries suffered the same
economic calamity at the same time, giving up the power to vary the exchange
rate would be no great loss. But if countries are affected differently by an
economic event - such as an oil shock or German unification - the desired
response may not be the same and therefore the costs of tying monetary
policies together high.
What does the evidence suggest about the costs and benefits of this
trade-off? The US is not free from regional swings in the fortunes of
individual states. But US state unemployment rates do not stay high for long
 -the US does not have persistent high or low unemployment regions. The main
reason is the very high level of migration between US states, much higher
than between British regions, let alone between European countries.
Region-specific economic shocks are more common in Europe than in the US.
Research co-ordinated by Mr Barry Eichengreen at the University of
California at Berkeley finds there tends to be more variation in economic
growth rates across European countries than US states.
This pattern does not hold for different combinations of European countries.
The European 'core' (Germany, France, Denmark and the Benelux countries)
looks much more like the US.
The risk - especially for the poorer southern European countries - is that
monetary union would carry with it a high political cost: high unemployment
and slow growth.
To argue that the single market requires a single currency in order to work
may be putting the cart before the horse. The single market may, in fact, be
a necessary forerunner of any monetary union because it would encourage the
greater economic integration, labour mobility and convergence of living
standards without which a single currency would prove too painful for some.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
