<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Life in the Single Market: Crash programme on VAT software -
The panic as exporters prepare to meet EC statistical demands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Mirams, marketing director at International Software Marketing,
found time to answer the telephone, but with difficulty. 'The world seems to
have gone mad,' he said. 'People are panicking at the last moment.'
The panic had been widely expected. Mr Mirams' company, a subsidiary of
software group JBA, is one of a clutch of software houses across Europe
doing hectic business as companies come belatedly to terms with the new VAT
regulations with which they are now compelled to comply.
The list includes major multinationals including the US-owned Dun &amp;
Bradstreet Software, private companies with an international presence such
as the UK's Coda, and fast expanding national champions like SAP of Germany.
The threat of legal action against companies failing to meet the new
reporting requirements seems to be concentrating minds wonderfully. The
regulations are designed to do away with the paperwork that causes delays at
border crossings.
But they demand new and comprehensive statistical records of the movements
of goods and lists of sales to companies in the Community.
The most important new documents are the European Sales List (ESL), which
details exports to people registered for VAT in other member states, and the
Supplementary Statistical Declaration (SSD) which provides data for the
Community's new trade statistics system.
The most effective way of providing the new statistics is to extract them
automatically from a company's comp-uterised accounting system; detailed
changes to the software which are neither quick nor easy to carry out are
required, however.
A survey late last year by Andersen Consulting showed that UK companies
believed their most serious challenge to be adapting their computer systems
to generate the required information.
The difficulties are exacerbated by lack of appreciation of the difficulties
and a traditional reluctance among managers to deal with export issues.
'It has all been left to Fred in the Portacabin with his typewriter,' says
Mr Mirams. Andersen's survey showed that across Europe 40 per cent of
companies are still unready for the new regime.
Software packages are one answer; among the dozen or so UK companies
providing software which meet some or all of the new requirements are
Albacore Systems, Computer Traffic, Fraser Williams Logistics, Langdon
Systems, Telesmart and Vistec.
ISM's product was developed by Sitpro, the UK organis-ation concerned with
the simplification of international trade procedures. It runs on a personal
computer. At a cost of about Pounds 4,600 for a single user it will generate
all the necessary documentation. Mr Mirams is unwilling to quote sales
figures but says the company has more than doubled its turnover this year.
But estimating the size of the market for the new VAT software across Europe
is complicated. Some 30,000 UK companies will have to submit detailed VAT
returns but many of these will have modular accounting systems to which the
new software can be linked without substantial mod-ifications.
The new regulations are not necessarily a source of windfall profits for
software houses, however. Those supplying mainframe accounting packages will
have to spend rather than make money.
The terms of their maintenance contracts with customers stipulates that new
software to meet legal requirements has to be provided free.
Mr Steve Lenehan, brand manager at Tetra, a leading accounting software
supplier, points out that the company has spent Pounds 350,000 in copying
new software for distribution to its customers and sent out 110,000 sheets
of documentation.
Mr David Turner of Coda says the company has spent more on modifications
than it will recoup in fees. 'It is the first time in the recent history of
accounting software that changes have had to be made because of legal
requirements.'
The software suppliers now have a brief breathing space. Entirely new
software will be needed before 1997, when a Community-wide, harmonised VAT
system is planned.
</TEXT>
