<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Europe 1993: Roman emperor Caesar Augustus founded Europe's
first single market, stretching from north Africa to Britain. Since then,
Europe's political boundaries have ebbed back and forth with the tides of
the continent's turbulent history. On this page, the FT presents the latest
reshuffle of the Euro-pack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Jacques Delors is not the first European leader with grand ambitons. Uniting
Europe economically, as well as politically, has been a goal of the powerful
for centuries.
Charlemagne, Barbarossa, Charles V, Napoleon and Hitler all belong on the
list of continental European rulers who have tried to build and maintain a
trans-European empire, although using more coercive methods than today's
politicians.
Yet few have managed to translate their conquests into an integrated economy
within which trade flows freely. And, so far, nobody has succeeded as well
as the Romans.
Octavian, heir of Julius Caesar, the conqueror of Gaul, is the true father
of Europe's single market. After his victory over Antony and Cleopatra at
Actium in 31 BC, it was Octavian, as the Emperor Augustus, who consolidated
Rome's vast European empire. Stretching from Egypt in the south-east to
Britain in the north-west, the empire of Augustus and his successors was an
economic, as well as a military, triumph.
'The Roman Empire created a vast area, with a single currency and low
customs barriers, in which commerce was hindered by neither pirates nor
frontiers and was aided by an elaborate network of roads and protected
harbours', the Times Atlas of World History declares.
Yet no single market can be trans-European without the Germans. Only
following the barbarian invasions of the 5th and 6th centuries, which
brought the Roman empire to an end, could modern Europe emerge.
Many subsequent conquerors have tried to create an integrated European
economy along Roman lines. None has succeeded. Only the second half of this
century, after ruinous conflicts among the European Great Powers, have
aspirations to build a new Roman Empire begun to look realisable.
Jean Monnet was the French architect of this new Europe. He was the
inspiration behind the Schuman Plan, which led to the European Coal and
Steel Community, formed in 1952 by Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg,
West Germany, France and Italy. This laid the foundations for the Treaty of
Rome, ratified in 1957, and the European Economic Community.
The EC has grown in memberhsip, scope and ambition over the last 40 years.
It is still some distance from creating a politically integrated community.
The Maastricht treaty's plans for a monetary union and greater defence
co-operation envisage a united Europe.
Yet the goals of Maastricht are still aspirations. The EC's greatest
tangible achievement to date is the Single European Act. Nurtured by EC
Commission President Jacques Delors, it forms the legislative basis for
Europe's second single market.
</TEXT>
