<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / 'Treaty of hope' signed by Bush and Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HUMANITY'S largest step back from the nuclear arms race was formally agreed
in Moscow yesterday by presidents Boris Yeltsin of Russia and George Bush of
the US.
The Start 2 treaty promises, over the next decade, to cut the two countries'
arsenals of strategic missiles to one-third of their present levels.
'I would call this treaty a treaty of hope,' said Mr Yeltsin, speaking in
the Kremlin after signing the agreement. Mr Bush matched his rhetoric by
speaking of standing 'at the threshold of a new world of hope'. Like the
Russian president, he said it represented the fulfilment of dreams which had
until recently seemed unrealisable.
Mr Yeltsin appeared vigorous and genial throughout the public parts of the
two-day event. He said Mr Victor Chernomyrdin, the new prime minister, would
continue economic reforms with 'the same cabinet' as had served Mr Yegor
Gaidar, his predecessor. He also promised to continue to back the US-United
Nations line of sanctions on Yugoslavia, in spite of dissent within his
parliament on both issues.
He said he was 'absolutely confident' that the Supreme Soviet would ratify
the treaty (as it had ratified Start 1 last November). However, Ukraine,
which with Belarus and Kazakhstan still holds strategic weapons, has not yet
ratified Start 1 - necessary before Start 2 can be implemented.
It is seen by the US as dragging its feet dangerously on the issue, although
yesterday Ukraine's president Leonid Kravchuk predicted that his parliament
would ratify Start 1.
Both Ukraine and neighbouring Belarus have bases housing bombers capable of
delivering nuclear missiles. Ukraine has been adamant that these bases,
though nominally controlled by the Commonwealth of Indepen-dent States, are
under its control.
Mr Bush assured Mr Yeltsin that Mr Bill Clinton, to whom he cedes office in
two weeks, backed the treaty and was committed to 'keeping relations with
Russia on the same high plane they are already on'.
Mr Yeltsin said he wanted to meet Mr Clinton soon after the President-elect
takes office on January 20. But Mr Clinton, flying home to Little Rock from
a holiday in South Carolina, said no date had yet been set for a meeting
with the Russian leader.
The treaty, codifying the agreement reached between the two presidents in
June last year in Washington, lays down a series of reductions over two
phases - the first ending seven years after Start 1 comes into force, the
second ending at the latest in 2003.
The number of strategic nuclear missile warheads held by either side will
not exceed 4,250 at the end of the first phase and 3,500 by the year 2003,
while intercontinental ballistic missiles with multiple warheads will be cut
entirely - signalling the end of the SS-18s deployed in the former Soviet
Union, a long-standing US goal. Submarine-launched ballistic missiles,
counted separately, will not exceed 1,750 warheads on either side.
One US official said yesterday that the cutting of the SS-18s and partial
destruction of their silos 'removes once and for all that dreaded thing, the
first strike'. In addition, 100 bombers will be 're-oriented' to
conventional roles, and transferred to conventional bases. New verification
procedures have been agreed, including a limited inspection right for
Russian officials of America's B2 'Stealth' bomber.
George Graham adds from Washington: In the US, senior senators from both
parties said they expected the Start 2 agreement to win ratification in
Congress.
Senator Joseph Biden, the Democratic chairman of the Senate judiciary
committee - which has jurisdiction over treaty ratifications - said his
concern was not with the treaty, but with the prospect that it might not be
implemented if the US did not do more to help the Russian government with
its economic reforms. 'I think we have been almost derelict in doing the
things we could be doing,' Mr Biden said.
Page 11
