<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Management: Tomorrow's leaders need to get up and go - Paul
Evans says that experience of working abroad is vital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A question companies frequently ask is: 'How can we develop the
Euro-manager?' I answer that the idea of a supra-national polyglot is as
illusory as that of a supra-national European union.
But what the single European market will do is to make it easier for
executives to develop the qualities that any business leader needs to cope
in a world where things have to be done better, cheaper and faster. And the
experience of managing in a different culture may be the best way of
developing global leadership talent.
The internationalisation of management is not simply a matter of ensuring
broad national representation on management teams, though that may be a
by-product. Languages help, but that is not the central issue. Nor is it a
question of developing some mythical international superperson.
The leaders I admire all tell me that they had a stretching assignment at an
early age. The time-tested formula is to find good people and then put them
in a position where they have to get results through people who think
differently from them, and who have more expertise - in other words, a
position where they have to lead.
Today the emphasis has shifted from cross-functional experience to
international experience. Dupont is a good example. Its norm for high
potential executives is: 'International experience is obligatory;
cross-functional experience is desirable and cross-divisional experience may
sometimes be necessary.' That would apply to companies of the calibre of
Shell, Unilever, Nestle, Ciba-Geigy and ABB.
A study by Kevin Barham and his colleagues at Ashridge Management College in
the UK showed that executives who successfully completed international
assignments excelled in a number of managerial competences: championing
international strategy (visioning the future), cross-border co-ordination
(handling international teams) and acting as cultural change agents (digging
below the surface and dealing with critical dilemmas).
Internationalisation is also a question of ensuring that managers have what
my colleague Yves Doz calls 'perspective'. Shell, IBM and Unilever want
local managers to run local businesses. But these companies would not trust
a local until that person had proven him or herself in a headquarters or
regional staff role.
But international management development is not just a tool to cultivate
individual managers. It can also give a company what Shell calls 'glue' or
'cohesion'.
Shell's organisational philosophy is to give autonomy to local operating
companies while acting as a tightly co-ordinated group. As Lo Van Wachem,
the former chairman of the group, said: 'There are three things that hold
these autonomous companies together. The first is the common logo. The
second is common financial systems. And the third and most important source
of cohesion is management development - close attention to career
development.'
Most corporations give at least token acknowledgement to internationalising
management. However, a 1989 survey of leading US corporations by Korn, Ferry
with Columbia Business School found only 6 per cent reporting that foreign
assignments were essential for senior executives, with 49 per cent believing
foreign assignments to be immaterial.
So why the disparity? The answer in part is that few such companies are
global and few have understood the connection between international
experience and leadership.
Another part of the problem lies with today's generation of CEOs, many of
whose international experience is patchy.
If I and my colleagues read the signals correctly, CEOs will be the next
rank in the hierarchy to come under fire. During the 1980s the
responsibility for strategy was largely devolved to business units. And in
today's flatter organisations, leaders in the middle are assuming ever
greater responsibilities.
I see a lot of disquiet among CEOs who are confronting issues such as the
role of top management in an age of global competition. And how does top
management add value to the corporation?
Many will be replaced by the new generation of leaders who can answer these
questions; whether they are German or British, Bangladeshi or Chinese
doesn't matter.
These coming top managers will be better leaders, with depth of perspective,
breadth of vision and an ability to thrive on complexity, all nurtured and
put to the test by their international experiences.
The author is Professor of Organisational Behaviour at Insead at
Fontainbleau, France.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
