<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / State blamed for snags in training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has given insufficient weight to social and economic needs in
some old industrial towns and cities, a report by Salford University
Business Services says.
The authors say that this has affected funding to Training and Enterprise
Councils (Tecs) - one of which commissioned the report - and made it harder
to restructure a local economy and improve training. Tecs deliver government
training schemes in England and Wales.
Subs, an independent consultancy attached to the university, has produced an
indexed league table of quality-of-life indicators allowing Tec funding to
be weighted for special difficulties. The work has been done by two
economists, Mr Jim Twomey and Professor Neville Topham.
They have not been allowed to disclose which Tec commissioned the work, but
their indexing system has impressed other Tecs in tough areas which are now
seeking similar advice to argue for more public funds.
Taking greater account of economic and social deprivation ought to mean more
funds for enterprise training and local initiatives in areas with the
greatest difficulties. Tecs using the Subs indices will have objective
criteria to argue their case.
Topping the league table for best quality of life are the Tec areas covering
Hertfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Milton Keynes, Surrey and the Thames Valley.
The bottom five of 75 in England are City and Inner London North,
Merseyside, Birmingham, East Lancashire and Bradford.
There is a cluster of blackspots involving seven Tecs in Merseyside, Greater
Manchester and Lancashire. Birmingham and Greater Nottingham are also among
the most difficult Tec areas, while there is another cluster of four
blackspots in Greater London.
The Salford analysis of how things are changing presents an even bleaker
picture. Quality of life appears to be improving most rapidly in the Tec
areas of Milton Keynes, the Thames Valley, Surrey, Hertfordshire and the
Heart of England; and falling fastest in City and Inner London North,
Tyneside, Wearside, Teesside and Merseyside - all of them with old,
inner-urban areas with narrow economic bases and high unemployment.
Prof Topham said: 'Future resource allocations should take account of the
backdrop against which individual Tecs have to work.'
Quality of Life and Tec Areas. Salford University Business Services. Pounds
195.
