<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Auditing rules welcomed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE QUARTERS of accountants believe the new self-regulatory mechanisms for
auditors have improved the quality of their auditing, an academic survey
reports.
Only 5 per cent of their clients have noticed any change, though, except for
an increase in fees, since audit regulation was introduced by the
professional accountancy bodies in October.
The findings come in an analysis of the experiences of 160 practitioners by
Ms Stella Fearnley of Southampton University and Mr Michael Page of
Portsmouth University.
Accountancy firms said audit regulation had helped them enhance standards of
work with more systematic recording of work performed, changes in audit
methods, better planning and more staff training.
They said audit regulation was costing a significant amount. Set-up costs
for firms with three or fewer partners were Pounds 4,900 on average and
recurring fixed costs were estimated at Pounds 3,400, most of which
represented lost time. They said little had been recovered through fees to
clients.
Four fifths called for the abolition of the statutory audit for smaller
companies but most wanted some remaining safeguards to preserve the quality
of the financial information presented.
The study reflects the conclusions published last month in the official
report to the Department of Trade and Industry from the three chartered
accountancy bodies covering the UK.
It shows that only 11 of the 158 randomly chosen auditors visited in the
first year met all 13 quality control tests drawn up and emphasised that
there were 'procedural shortfalls' in many firms.
There are an estimated 10,200 auditors registered with the three chartered
accountancy institutes and a further 1,000 with the Chartered Association of
Certified Accountants. But 160 firms between them audit all listed
companies, with eight firms auditing three quarters of them. Only 20 firms
each audit more than five listed companies. Two thirds of auditors are sole
practitioners and 90 per cent have four or fewer partners.
</TEXT>
