<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Labour Research criticises pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH STATE pensions are among the least generous in the European
Community according to Labour Research, the independent trade union and
labour movement magazine.
A study by the organisation says arrangements in the UK are worse than in
any EC state except Ireland.
Labour Research says there are two main types of scheme in the EC - one
linked to earnings and the other flat-rate. The UK operates a mixture of the
two.
It says countries operating fully earnings-related schemes include Belgium,
with a top-rate entitlement of 60 per cent of earnings, France (50 per
cent), and Germany (60 per cent). Occupational pensions may face 'disaster'
unless reforms are made to the law in the wake of the Maxwell scandal, the
TUC warns today.
Its submission to the Goode Committee, which is reviewing pension law,
includes proposals for replacement of trust law with a single pensions act
and the separation of scheme assets from those of the employer.
Labour Research, 78 Blackfriars Rd, London SE1 8HF. Pounds 2.40 plus
postage.
</TEXT>
