<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Boardrooms look to their honours: The prime minister's
changes to the awards system could upset the expectations of many business
people
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS a fin de siecle feeling in Whitehall last week at the ending of
automatic honours for civil servants, career diplomats and politicians.
It should perhaps have been echoed in boardrooms across the country because
Mr John Major's overhaul of the honours system, which will affect the next
list in June, will have an impact well beyond officialdom.
Awards to figures in industry are not quite as routine and hierarchical as
honours for mandarins, but the government still looks after the business
establishment. More than half of the chairmen of the UK's top 100 companies
are knights or peers, and many other senior figures in those organisations
have received honours related to their status and length of service.
A statement on the results of the honours system review is expected in the
next three months. Downing Street has cautioned against expecting dramatic
alterations in the way awards are given, saying that changes will be
incremental. Over time, however, even the gradual shift envisaged will have
a striking effect. In 20 years' time the House of Lords might look very
different from its present appearance.
For a start, it might contain fewer business representatives. Mr Major has
created only two life peers from industry, and one of them, Lord Cooke, was
at the request of the Ulster Unionists.
The contrast in that respect with Mrs Thatcher's practice was heightened by
the awarding of three life peerages to businessmen in her resignation
honours list in 1991.
A further change from the Thatcher years may well be the expansion of the
list of those deemed acceptable for honours. Just as Mr Major gave political
awards to some Tory MPs snubbed by Mrs Thatcher, so he may be willing to
look beyond an inner circle of business leaders that was favoured by his
predecessor and included figures such as Lord Hanson; Lord Sterling, the
chairman of P&amp;O; and Lord King, the chairman of British Airways.
There are also signs that political activity might not be what it once was
as a way through the honours system. Although senior figures in generous
corporate donors to Tory party funds, such as United Biscuits, will probably
continue to receive awards, linkage may well be less immediate.
Mr Stanley Kalms, the chairman of Dixons, who was a cheerleader in one of Mr
Major's election campaign extravaganzas, has not yet received what many
might regard as his reward, while Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy, the chairman and
chief executive of Kingfisher, the retail group, was knighted in last week's
list.
Although Kingfisher has given money to the Tories, it has also supported
Labour events, and the award seems to owe more to Sir Geoffrey's involvement
in initiatives such as Business in the Community.
If the honours system does tilt further towards recognition of the business
community's contribution to the government's rather than the Tory party's
activities, in a few years' time Mr Richard Branson, chairman of the Virgin
Group, might well be celebrating a knighthood or life peerage for assisting
the franchising of British Rail passenger services.
Downing Street has given a strong hint that the honours review will lead to
closer links between an award and someone's broader role in the community.
There may be more awards such as the knighthood for Mr Paul Nicholson, the
chairman of Vaux group, the Sunderland-based brewer and hotels operator,
specifically for services to industry and to the public.
One aide said: 'The prime minister is keen to make the system reflect areas
where individuals make a contribution, rather than necessarily just do a
job. The contribution can be within the job, which may go beyond the job
specification, but equally may be beyond that in charity or voluntary work.'
He added that in the case of someone running an organisation, the
contribution might be in being flexible enough to enable their employees to
play an active part in the local community.
If the criteria for business honours shift in that direction, one likely
candidate might be Ms Anita Roddick, the managing director of the Body Shop
group, for her involvement with the homeless through the newspaper The Big
Issue.
Whether revamping the honours system makes it better at recognising
individual merit will not be clear for some time. But if the prime minister
is seeking to send an early signal that the worst aspects of politicking and
Buggins' turnery have been removed, he could do worse than ponder a life
peerage for Sir Bob Reid, the chairman of British Rail, whose concern for
BR's social role has led him to be both publicly and privately critical of
the privatisation plans.
</TEXT>
