<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Companies 'open to option claims'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of companies may be vulnerable to compensation claims over
share-option schemes from dismissed employees, Mr David Cohen, of City
lawyers Paisner &amp; Co, a leading adviser on share option schemes, says.
Since 1980 more than 2m employees, mainly managers and executives, have
received share options, and with the recent growth in executive unemployment
they are becoming an increasingly important part of a dismissed employee's
compensation.
When employees are unfairly dismissed, it has been held that they would not
be entitled to extra compensation for loss of share options. That belief, Mr
Cohen says, has been overturned by a recent verdict of the Employment Appeal
Tribunal in a case involving Texas Homecare, the DIY chain.
Mr Cohen says: 'That decision appears to indicate that even an option which
has only recently been issued - in the Texas case the option was only six
months old - will give rise to a compensation entitlement.'
Option valuation, he adds, is an imprecise exercise and one that few, if
any, tribunals are equipped to tackle.
</TEXT>
