<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Fall in output predicted to continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OUTPUT BY manufacturers will continue to decline over the next few months,
the Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply forecasts.
A survey published today by the institute, which represents purchasing
managers in manufacturing, shows that prices of imported raw materials
increased sharply in December for the third successive month, as a result of
the fall in the pound since Britain left the European exchange rate
mechanism on September 16.
Another report published today, by Infolink, a business information company,
indicates that the outlook for the consumer sector may be brighter. It says
demand for credit by consumers for purchases of cars and retail goods rose
in November for the second successive month.
An index published by the purchasing institute showing levels of economic
activity among member companies fell slightly to 49.2 in December from 49.5
in November. This indicates that an imminent upturn in manufacturing is
unlikely.
Companies last month reported a slight increase in new orders, with export
orders in particular benefiting from sterling's devaluation. Much of the
rise in orders was seasonal, related to an expansion in demand ahead of
Christmas.
Companies continued to run down stocks in December. The number of companies
sacking employees 'continues to substantially outweigh those recruiting',
the institute says.
The weak state of the European economy may hold back a significant upturn in
the UK, according to the latest world economic forecasts from Oxford
Economic Forecasting, an economic consultancy.
Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply, Easton House, Easton on the
Hill, Stamford, Lincolnshire.
Consumer Credit Report. Infolink, 2 South End, Croydon.
World Economic Prospects. Oxford Economic Forecasting, Templeton College,
Oxford.
