<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Major stance on sterling is applauded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POSSIBILITY that Britain's separation from the European exchange rate
mechanism will end in divorce may have increased yesterday after Mr John
Major appeared to attach new conditions for sterling's re-entry and said
that that would not happen for at least another year.
The prime minister's reference to linking sterling in a modified form of the
ERM to the yen and the dollar was seen by several commentators as
impractical, on the ground that it would require an implausibly large
stepping up of co-operation on economic matters between Japan, the US and
Europe.
Mr Major's ruling out of sterling rejoining the ERM this year was applauded
as realistic by several members of the Treasury's new economic advisory
panel and by industry representatives. They said it improved the prospect of
a UK recovery.
One view was that if Britain proposed as a condition of ERM re-entry even an
informal method of linking European currencies with the yen and dollar, the
result might be a permanent block on the UK's re-joining the mechanism. The
UK left the ERM in mid September after widespread selling of the pound.
Mr Andrew Britton, director of the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research and a member of the Treasury's seven-strong economic panel, which
meets for the first time this month, said: 'Mr Major's remark makes him
appear not to be all that keen on a European monetary policy. It throws
doubt as to whether he really wants Britain back in the ERM.'
Mr David Currie, head of economic forecasting at the London Business School
and another panel member, said: 'In view of the marked disagreements (on
economic policy) between Japan, the US and Germany, it would be extremely
difficult to adapt the ERM to introduce a link with the yen and the dollar.'
But there was a general welcome for the idea of Britain putting off re-entry
to the ERM for at least another year. Such a move would appear to rule out
during 1993 any government-inspired effort to engineer a higher sterling
exchange rate, in a development that would permit a relatively relaxed
policy on interest rates and so strengthen recovery prospects. Since Britain
left the ERM, sterling has depreciated by about 12 per cent against other
main currencies and the government has cut base rates by 3 percentage points
to 7 per cent.
Professor Wynne Godley of Cambridge University, a long-time critic of UK
economic policy and a member of the Treasury advisory panel, said: 'I
welcome Mr Major's comments. We are seeing an enormous outbreak of good
sense.'
Others warned that in the long term industry would require a way to limit
changes in the value of sterling, irrespective of the future for the ERM and
whether Britain was a member.
Mr Andrew Sentance, head of economics at the Confederation of British
Industry and another member of the Treasury's economic panel, said:
'Industry has not lost interest in exchange rate stability.'
Sir Anthony Gill, chairman and chief executive of Lucas, the engineering
components group, said: 'Industry has managed to live with currency
fluctuations in the past and will do so again, even if Britain stays out of
the ERM. I'm not too concerned about the UK failing to rejoin over the next
year, but longer-term it would be very useful to see greater stability in
currency rates.'
Mr Major's comments are unlikely to end the broader debate about whether
Britain's rejoining the ERM - possibly after enough time has elapsed to
permit a UK recovery and for the German Bundesbank to cut its interest rates
and so reduce some of the general strains within the mechanism - is in the
UK's best interests.
Mr Tim Congdon, head of economic consultancy Lombard Street Research and a
fierce ERM opponent who is another member of the Treasury's economic panel,
said: 'I am pleased that Britain is not going back (to the ERM) this year.
But I am disappointed that the government is even contemplating rejoining
later on.'
As far as much of industry is concerned, whatever the longer-term aspects of
possible ERM re-entry, there is widespread welcome for the benefits of a
lower sterling exchange rate.
PRIME MINISTER'S MAIN POINTS
In his interview with Sir David Frost, Mr John Major said:
The UK would not return to the European exchange rate mechanism in 1993
There might be a need for international co-operation to create a
relationship between European currencies, the US dollar and the yen, if
sterling returned to a managed exchange rate system
He expected 'gentle' growth of 1 per cent in 1993, accelerating in 1994
Unemployment might not lag so far behind recovery as it did after the
recession of the early 1980s
About two thirds of the public-sector borrowing requirement was cyclical and
there would be a 'benevolent change' once the economy recovered
The UK could not afford to take risks with inflation.  Low inflation and low
interest rates were needed to stimulate investment
The government's aim was to have the minimum level of taxation, particularly
direct taxation
The government was not retreating on British Rail privatisation but was
following through the proposals published last summer.
</TEXT>
<XX>
