<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Bucking the trend: Eternal optimist plans expansion - A
specialist that has thrived since it was bought by its management on the eve
of the truck market collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST YEAR was the third in a row that the UK's commercial vehicle industry
would rather forget. For much of the year, UK truck sales continued a
headlong plunge to market levels rarely experienced since the second world
war.
There are at last tentative signs of recovery, though: sales of trucks over
3.5 tonnes have risen slightly, on a year-on-year basis, in each of the past
five months, and the trend is expected to strengthen this year.
It is, nevertheless, an extraordinarily gloomy background, but one against
which one manufacturer expects to announce sharply increased profits and
expanded sales and production for last year.
No less remarkable is that the company concerned floated itself successfully
on the London Stock Exchange little more than two months ago and has seen
barely more than three years elapse since becoming the subject of a Pounds
27.3m management buy-out almost on the eve of the collapse of the truck
market.
That Trinity Holdings - the maker of Dennis fire engines, dustcarts and
other specialised trucks and buses, as well as of Duple (Metsec) bus body
kits - has defied recession so strongly is a source of considerable
satisfaction to Mr Geoffrey Hollyhead, its chairman and chief executive, who
led the 1989 buy-out.
Market analysts expect that in a few weeks' time he will report that Trinity
achieved an operating profit of more than Pounds 8m in the financial year to
the end of this month. That compares with the previous year's figure of
Pounds 5.6m, and Pounds 4.8m in the first year after the buy-out from its
previous owner, Hestair.
Turnover has also risen steadily from Pounds 66m in the first year after the
buy-out to Pounds 82m the following year, with 1992's results expected to
exceed Pounds 100m. Only last month, Trinity won a Pounds 38m order from Sri
Lanka for its Duple (Metsec) subsidiary to supply 2,500 bus bodies.
That has provided a further boost for the investors who took up Trinity's
offer of 25m 10p shares at 120p a share in October.
Given that the Stock Market at the time was in recession-battered disarray,
both the flotation itself and the take-up - the issue was 2.3 times
oversubscribed - looked like a brave decision, particularly as the
engineering sector generally has been among the worst-hit by the recession.
But with Trinity's shares trading at 166p at the close last week, and
growing bullishness from the government and industry about this year's
economic prospects, the company's concerns are now very much with the future
and growth, particularly in exports.
In spite of the depressed conditions in some of the many market niches in
which Trinity specialises, the group's total vehicle production has
continued to rise.
Production at Trinity, which is based at Warwick and has plants at
Worcester, Halifax, Tipton and Guildford. reached 914 in the first three
quarters of last year, up from 690 in the comparable 1991 period, and output
continued to accel-erate in the final quarter.
With the order from Sri Lanka, Trinity expects to build further on export
activities, which already account for a third of its turnover. In that
regard, Trinity is building on the long-established presence of Dennis - one
of the UK's oldest vehicle makers through a succession of ownerships - in
Third World and other overseas markets outside Europe.
Some of Trinity's growth has come from acquisition, notably Reliance
Mercury, which specialises in dockyard and airport towing vehicles, and
Carmichael, the producer of airfield crash tenders and rapid-intervention
vehicles.
But a significant amount is expected to come from heavy investments in new
products. Among them are a new generation of chassis for the Dart, the UK's
best-selling bus, and a new range of refuse disposal vehicles.
Some Pounds 10m has gone into new manufacturing facilities at Guildford,
Surrey. Not content with traditional export markets such as Hong Kong,
Trinity has also begun a sales push into continental Europe, starting with
the Benelux countries.
At the same time, tighter inventory and other management controls are
attributed by Trinity's management team to the sharply improved financial
performance of the company. They are seen by Mr Hollyhead - a self-professed
'eternal optimist' - as putting the company in good shape for what is
expected to be a strong recovery in two of its main UK market sectors:
refuse vehicles, and buses and coaches.
Both have been affected not so much by recession as by the the government's
policies on privatisation and deregulation. Local-authority tendering and
the deregulation of bus and coach services - initiated in the 1980s - have
had knock-on effects in terms of the abolition of grants to bus buyers and a
reluctance to invest in new local-authority equipment.
Trinity believes that such disincentives - which have reduced demand for
such vehicles by up to a half - are now disappearing rapidly, with all that
that entails for growth this year.
</TEXT>
