<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Overspend by BBC may rise to Pounds 90m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS ARE growing that the potential overspend at the BBC is substantially
more than previously admitted publicly.
The BBC has conceded that because of 'a series of reporting and control
failures' there had been an overspend of Pounds 38m in 1991-92 at BBC
Television. The overall BBC budget was, however, balanced by the end of that
financial year. In addition, BBC Television has ordered Pounds 20m cuts to
deal with a potential overspend in this financial year but admitted that the
total would be higher. A further Pounds 12m in savings has already been
asked for.
Senior BBC staff believe the total involved over the two years might be more
than Pounds 90m, although the figure is not confirmed. There are concerns
that no one knows precisely the state of BBC Television finances and whether
all the 'reporting and control failures' have been dealt with.
A governors' audit committee chaired by Lord Barnett, vice-chairman of the
BBC governors and a former chief secretary to the Treasury, found there was
no evidence of fraud.
As a result of the overspend, the BBC is believed to be approaching its
Pounds 200m borrowing limit.
The issue will mean a difficult debut for Mr John Birt, the new BBC
director-general who has taken over from Sir Michael Checkland. Mr Birt is
looking for a Pounds 50m contingency fund, partly in case there are any
unexpected recurrences of financial difficulties in the 1993-94 financial
year.
The atmosphere of cuts and savings at BBC Television will make it more
difficult for Mr Birt to realise his vision of a BBC which offers a more
distinctive service which is less reliant on cheap, imported programmes.
Distinctive UK-made programmes will cost more than imported programmes. Mr
Birt hopes to make substantial savings through Producer Choice. The scheme
gives producers the right to buy services in the external market if they are
more cost-effective.
</TEXT>
