<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Distance learning MBA launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW TYPE of distance-learning master of business administration degree for
financial specialists is to be offered worldwide by a company set up by the
University of Wales at Bangor and Manchester Business School.
The degree - which the two institutions say is unique - has been designed
for English-speaking managers in sectors such as banking, insurance,
accountancy, building societies or corporate financial control.
The MBA will be awarded by the University of Wales but be run by the
company, which is called the Institute of Financial Management. The course
has been designed by Manchester's Centre for Banking and Financial Services
and Bangor's School of Accounting, Banking and Economics.
A network of study support centres around the world will enable students to
take the degree from anywhere in Australia, Africa, India, South America,
the Caribbean, Canada, Europe, the Middle East, South East Asia or the Far
East.
The course, which is spread over 30 months, will contain several short
periods of full-time study, but most work will be done part-time in parallel
with a normal job. It is open to graduates or people with equivalent
banking, insurance or building society qualifications, or relevant
management experience.
