<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Economics Notebook: Time to discuss a Europe-wide monetary
policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT has been done more by accident than design.
But the European Community today is more to the taste of the UK government
than at any time since June 1988 when EC leaders in Hanover launched the
community down the road to economic and monetary union.
The single market, although incomplete and imperfect, has been brought
closer than many sceptics thought possible when it was launched in 1985.
The recent upheavals in the European exchange rate mechanism have dimmed the
prospects of Emu by the end of the century.
Indeed, if the ERM falls prey to continuing strains, resulting in the break
of the D-Mark-French franc link, the outlook for Emu would be so bleak that
the EC might turn with greater vigour to completing the single market.
But there is another scenario, which could threaten the position of the City
of London as an international financial centre and demands serious thinking
about the future of the Bank of England.
Suppose that the ERM, against the expectations of many commentators and
operators in the foreign exchange markets, survives the coming months with
the D-Mark-French franc relationship intact, or even strengthened.
Then the French government and other EC countries such as Belgium would want
to push ahead as quickly as possible with Emu. The German Bundesbank,
although doubtful about Emu, would be keen to finalise details of a future
European monetary policy, just as in the months before the December 1991
Maastricht summit, it pushed for - and secured - agreement on statutes for
the proposed European central bank that are largely modelled on its own
Bundesbank law.
The possible shape of a future Europe-wide monetary policy is hardly
discussed in Britain. This may be understandable given the likelihood that
the UK will be outside the ERM for a lengthy period. But it is being
discussed in the remaining ERM countries as well as among EC central
bankers.
Already the Bundesbank is staking out positions that, if eventually
accepted, would put the City in a far less favourable monetary policy
environment than today. On December 17 last year, Mr Helmut Schlesinger, the
Bundesbank president, gave a lecture at Frankfurt university in which he
outlined his vision of a European monetary policy.
It would include:
money supply targets for Europe as part of a stringent counter-inflationary
policy. These targets would be similar to those used by the Bundesbank to
guide and justify its high interest rates during the past three years.
minimum reserve requirements - the absence of which has been one of London's
attractions as an international financial centre.
Germany's minimum reserve requirements help give the Bundesbank tight
control over the provision of liquidity to the banking system and have
helped slow down the process of financial innovation in Germany.
The Bundesbank wants minimum reserves in a Europe-wide monetary policy
because it fears that the lack of such an instrument would cause too much
emphasis to be placed on fine-tuning monetary policy: a criticism its
officials make privately of UK monetary policy.
One of Mr Schlesinger's goals is to safeguard any future European central
bank from having to worry about interest rates on a daily basis instead of
focusing on medium-term objectives such as money supply growth and the
ultimate goal of defeating inflation.
The Bundesbank also disapproves of the prominence given to
lender-of-last-resort responsibilities in Anglo-Saxon central bank policies.
If Mr Schlesinger and his successors have their way, any future European
central bank will be biased strongly against bailing out financial
institutions.
The interests of individual financial centres would be subordinated to the
European bank's paramount policy goal of price stability. If the German
vision of a European monetary policy is realised, a future financial crisis
could see banks or financial institutions in the City being allowed to go
under rather than being rescued to safeguard London's position as an
international financial centre.
These ramifications of a future EC monetary policy should be a matter of
debate in Britain. Also important is how much influence the Bank of England
can bring to bear in the discussions with Britain's EC partners on such
matters.
The Bank would hope to muster some allies - including perhaps France - to
help limit the Bundesbank's ambitions. But the UK is outside the ERM, a
factor that reduces the Bank's influence in EC affairs. The Bank also lacks
the clout that the Bundesbank has from independence. Unlike other EC central
banks, it has no grounds to believe that the government wants to give it
more freedom.
The Bank's court meets later this month for a preliminary, internal
discussion over the future of the Bank. The question of independence, or at
least greater operational freedom from the Treasury, is certain to be on the
agenda.
Last week, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, fired a shot across the court's
bows by again rejecting the idea that UK monetary policy should be
transferred to an independent Bank of England.
But the government is committed to ratifying the Maastricht treaty. If (and
they are admittedly big ifs) the ERM survives, Emu stays on the EC's agenda
and the UK parliament eventually accepts stage three of Emu, Britain will
have to accept an independent central bank at some time - and one which will
most likely be in Bonn rather than in London.
As the future of the City may be influenced by the Bank of England's status,
the debate about its future should be brought more into the open.
This should be possible now that the Treasury has a new policy of openness
and greater accountability. In the circumstances, the least Mr Lamont could
do would be to explain why he is so strongly opposed to an independent
central bank for Britain and detail the benefits that Britons gain from
keeping the Bank of England under his thumb.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311  Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment and Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 29
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT931-16927</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DADBPACHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Stock markets slow down on road to convergence / A look at
the impact of instability in Europe during the past year on equity
investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN investors no longer care where a company is based, Europe's stock
markets will finally have converged.
A year ago, that process looked well under way. Everything argued for
convergence: the imminence of the EC's single market; the steady progress
towards European monetary union, the increasing firmness of the exchange
rate mechanism; the negotiations to create a European Economic Area linking
Sweden, Switzerland and Austria to the 12. Big brokerage houses had
reorganised their research departments to carry out pan-European sectoral
analysis; equity strategists were wondering how to allocate pension fund
assets under Emu.
It seemed to be a question of when, not whether, European equity markets
would converge.
In the bond markets, many investors were already convinced. Arguing that Emu
would lead to equalisation of interest rates at around the German level,
convergence enthusiasts saw bargains in high-yielding European bond markets
such as the UK, Spain and Italy. Equity markets would follow the same path,
it seemed.
True, doubts persisted about how long convergence would take. The
institutional plumbing necessary for an integrated European stock market was
lacking. Substantial national differences in accounting and tax practices
remained.
On the other hand, there was solid factual underpinning for stock market
convergence, as the chart shows. In 1987, for example, all but two markets
showed double-digit divergences from the European mean. Spain out-performed
the European average by 35 per cent; Germany under-performed it by 27 per
cent.
By 1991, the markets were moving more closely together. Only one diverged by
more than 10 per cent from the average - Italy, which under-performed by 13
per cent. The others were clustered closely together, rarely out- or
under-performing by more than 5 per cent. Convergence seemed on its way.
A year later, these hopes have been badly damaged. Currency stability has
been undermined by devaluations by Britain, Italy, Sweden, Spain, Portugal,
Finland and Norway.
Equity markets have reacted to the devaluations by marking up shares sharply
in most of those countries, leading to noticeable differences of
performance. In 1992 as a whole, five out of eight big European equity
markets diverged from the average by more than 10 per cent, the largest such
group since 1987.
The devaluations were not the only forces at work. Switzerland said 'No' to
membership of the EEA; Denmark joined Britain in obtaining an escape route
from Emu; the once-smooth road from an ever-harder ERM to full-scale
monetary union looked strewn with obstacles.
None the less, some powerful trends continue to push in the direction of
convergence:
Company earnings. Diversification and the single European market are likely
to bring the earnings cycle among big European companies closer together. By
buying into the US, German and French companies have reduced their heavy
dependence on European markets. British companies have bought more heavily
into continental Europe, reducing their past emphasis on English-speaking
markets.
The progressive reduction of barriers to trade within the EC and the wider
EEA will also make European companies look more like each other. By managing
production and pricing on a pan-European basis, big companies are likely to
compete away each others' home market advantages. When every big business is
Europe-wide, all are likely to show similar results.
Valuation. European bourses are already starting to value those earnings
flows in a consistent way. 'Roughly comparable companies tend to be valued
pretty similarly,' says Mr Nick Stevenson, European equity strategies at
Warburg Securities. 'For example, Italian companies seem to be valued
roughly in line with northern European companies, and thus to look expensive
compared with local interest rates.'
Using valuation measures that minimise the differences between national
accounting and tax policies - such as the ratio of a company's share price
to its net cash flow - throws up striking similarities of valuation. Of the
30 European engineering companies covered by Warburg's analysts, for
instance, the prices of most lie between 3.8 and 5.8 times cash flow. In the
car industry, the big European makers are mostly valued at around 2.5 to 3
times cash flow. 'You can't actually say that certain markets value certain
companies in different ways,' says Mr Stevenson.
Investor attitudes. The growth of funded pensions schemes - until recently
largely an Anglo-Dutch phenomenon but now an increasingly important factor
in Switzerland and likely to prove so in France - is a powerful spur to
institutional investor power.
So is privatisation of state-owned financial institutions, already promised
in Italy and possible in France if a non-socialist government comes into
power in the spring elections.
A debate on corporate govern- ance is also under way in Germany. Though the
process will vary from country to country, fund managers are likely to press
for a similar agenda: transparent accounting, equal treatment for all
shareholders, proper takeover rules, a greater emphasis on shareholders'
interests and attention to profits rather than size.
Taken together, these forces will ensure that convergence continues despite
1992's setbacks. Mr Gordon Anderson, senior vice- president in charge of
global equity trading at Commerzbank in Frankfurt argues that the process
will take a long time, and it will probably not result, as some visionaries
believed a year or so ago, in a focus on pan-European sectors to the
exclusion of country or currency considerations.
'The country allocation comes first' for international investors, Mr
Anderson says. 'But they are already very interested in comparing Barclays,
for example, and Commerzbank.'
In time, he says, the relative weight given to the two axes of analysis,
country and sector, will shift - slowly, almost imperceptibly. But the
country decision will remain important.
Mr Reinhard Fischer - who covers German stocks from London for Paribas, the
French bank - says that convergence will be made longer and more arduous by
the effects of German re-unification. German managers will reverse their
progress towards more transparent accounting by dumping the bad news brought
about by re-unification into the 1992 financial year. Harmonising EC
corporate taxation will be harder because the bill for re-unification makes
cutting Germany's high corporate taxes much more difficult.
Perhaps the most important effect of 1992's upsets, however, is that it will
confirm investors in their habit of looking first at currencies and
countries, and only secondly at sectors and companies.
Commerzbank's Mr Anderson says: 'I've been in the business for 30 years  -
and it's as true as it's always been that if you get the currency judgment
right, you're likely to make money.' As long as investors profit from taking
that view, Europe's equity markets will not truly have converged.
</TEXT>
<XX>
