<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / German economics minister quits: Mollemann's departure comes
as fresh blow to coalition cabinet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Jurgen Mollemann resigned yesterday as German economics minister and
vice-chancellor, in a fresh blow to the stability of Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's three-party coalition.
His sudden and emotional departure followed his admission that he had
personally sanctioned and signed letters promoting a product manufactured by
a relation.
The decision opens a big gap in Mr Kohl's cabinet, already hurt by the
premature resignation of four other ministers in the past nine months,
including that of Mr Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the former foreign minister and
vice-chancellor, who was Mr Mollemann's mentor in the minority Free
Democratic party (FDP).
Mr Kohl had already promised to shuffle his cabinet in the last week of
January.
Mr Mollemann, who had hoped to become the next leader of the FDP, was not
particularly popular with his colleagues, not only in the opposition Social
Democrats (SPD) but also among Mr Kohl's Christian Democrats (CDU), for his
outspoken free-market views. However, his departure after 10 years in the
government was greeted officially with regret.
His demise follows press revelations that his ministerial notepaper had been
used to promote a security device for supermarket trolleys made in Cologne
by a company called Pro Invention, part-owned by a cousin of his wife,
Carola.
In a statement issued before Christmas, Mr Mollemann had claimed that blank
notepaper carrying his signature, intended for use when he was away from the
office, had been used without his knowledge for letters to leading
supermarket operators, urging them to look at the plastic token produced by
Pro Invention.
Yesterday, he admitted that he had been consulted about the letters by his
personal assistant, had agreed to their distribution on the grounds that
handicapped workers would be involved in the manufacture and had failed to
notice that the final letters made no mention of the handicapped.
'I did not lie,' he said yesterday after cutting short a holiday in the
Caribbean and consulting his colleagues in the leadership of the FDP. 'I
authorised the original statement in good conscience, and to the best of my
knowledge. But that does not lessen my self-reproach for having failed
adequately to ascertain the facts.'
Mr Mollemann, a former teacher who had risen to the top of the FDP largely
as a result of skilful public relations, turned on the German media for
exposing the affair and for hounding his wife and children in recent days.
He said he no longer intended to stand for leadership of the FDP when Mr
Otto Lambsdorff steps down this year, leaving the way open for his
colleague, Mr Klaus Kinkel, the foreign minister, to take over.
There has been speculation that Mr Kohl will try to appoint Ms Birgit
Breuel, head of the Treuhand privatisation agency in east Germany, as
economics minister in the coalition cabinet, although she is a member of his
own CDU.
Germany's enfant terrible bows out, Page 27
</TEXT>
