<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / The Lex Column: Equities exposed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
That leaves the equity market exposed. German shares have been valued above
their long-term trend for the last couple of years. Yet the impact of
falling profits only started to affect the stock market towards the end of
1992. With more unpleasant earnings shocks likely, any delay in interest
rate cuts could badly affect sentiment. This notion is reinforced by the
fact that bond yields have already fallen sharply in the expectation of
short-term rate reductions. So, even if the rate cuts come through, further
rallies in the bond market may be limited and thus would offer little
additional impetus to equities.
France, however, offers a nice contrast. Inflation is subdued and industry
is competitive, yet economic growth is being held back by the ERM-inspired
high interest rates. Both equities and bonds would benefit from a loosening
of monetary policy, and one way or another that is likely to happen in the
course of the year.
If the Bundesbank lowers rates in response to domestic German recession,
then pressure within the ERM will ease and French rates can fall. But if the
Bundesbank drags its heels, the mismatch between the monetary needs of
different continental economies will revive ERM pressures and either break
the ERM or force a significant rate cut. In either event France would get
the lower interest rates justified by domestic conditions. And that might
just make France the market to watch in 1993.
</TEXT>
