<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / The Lex Column: Good prospects
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
From an external investor's point of view, the good prospects in US Treasury
bonds, and to some extent shares, are gilded by the likely rise of the
dollar. By purchasing power measures the dollar is still cheap against
European currencies, and improving US growth is likely to increase the
dollar's attractions. With a strengthening currency and rising asset prices,
the US still looks fairly attractive.
The German economy is a much less pretty picture. High interest rates have
finally tipped the economy into recession, and the risks are that the
contraction will accelerate. Estimates of the cost of unification are still
rising and the policy stalemate between the fiscal and monetary authorities
seems likely to continue. At the same time there is a world surplus of
capital goods which form the backbone of Germany's exports. Inflation
pressures at home and devaluations by some of Germany's trading partners
have also made German goods less competitive.
What makes the German bind so tight is that inflation and strong monetary
growth have proved persistent. As a result monetary policy has been kept
tight by the Bundesbank, despite the deepening recession. The key to German
 -and indeed European - investment performance this year will be the timing
of eventual German interest rate cuts. And in the absence of tax increases
or a sudden slowing in the growth of the money supply, the risk is that the
Bundesbank will move more slowly than the market currently hopes.
</TEXT>
