<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / The Lex Column: American dream
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Fears of a large fiscal package from a Democratic administration weighed on
the US Treasury bond market in the run up to the presidential election. But
following President-elect Bill Clinton's victory the bond market rallied as
growth became more robust. The need for a large reflationary package has
thus been reduced. As a bonus, economic growth curbs the deficit directly by
increasing tax revenues and cutting social security spending.
Yet despite this improved supply picture real bond yields remain
historically high. The bond market may thus be expressing fears about future
inflation prospects, but for the foreseeable future US inflation is likely
to remain subdued. Monetary aggregates are under control, commodity prices
are weak, and with much of the expansion coming from productivity gains wage
pressures are unlikely to become a problem.
Indeed, although the burden of servicing debt has fallen for consumers,
unemployment may fall only slowly, and the relatively high level of
outstanding debt is likely to mute any consumer spending spree. While the
balance of probability favours US growth proving stronger than currently
expected, there is little chance of an outright inflationary boom.
Once that positive message begins to sink in, bond yields may well start to
fall. Which may in turn spark further modest gains in the equity market. The
performance of shares was disappointing in 1992, despite the market hitting
all-time highs. Valuations already discounted a substantial earnings
recovery, and rising money market rates late in the year raised fears that
the funds which had flowed out of deposits to support shares might start to
flow back.
If, however, the inflation outlook remains satisfactory and bond yields
continue to fall, the rise in money market rates may be partly reversed. And
unless growth proves much stronger than expected, official rates are
unlikely to rise before the tail end of 1993. Somewhat higher growth may
also lead to the earnings rebound being better than expected. Having cut
costs, the US corporate sector is strongly geared to economic recovery: an
additional 1 per cent on growth would add 10 per cent to earnings.
</TEXT>
