<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / The Lex Column: Tales of two markets
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is no small irony that much of Europe hovers in or near recession at the
start of 1993. In the minds of consumers and businessmen the much-heralded
single market adventure, which was to promote prosperity and trade, has been
overshadowed by falling demand and rising unemployment. In part that is due
to the world recession, which began in the Anglo-Saxon economies. But high
German interest rates are now the main drag on European growth. And while
the UK can now pursue an expansionary monetary policy free of its ERM
chains, most of continental Europe faces a bleak prospect until German rates
fall substantially.
By contrast the huge single market on the other side of the Atlantic is
faring much better. Low interest rates, a competitive dollar and wholesale
rationalisation of industries have finally combined to spark economic growth
in the US - much of it coming from increasing industrial investment. This
decoupling of economic prospects between the US and Europe suggests that
investment performance on either side of the Atlantic is likely to differ
widely in 1993.
</TEXT>
