<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Leading Article: Next steps in Somalia
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MILITARY intervention in Somalia was a necessary first step, but it was also
the easiest. Now the hard part begins: finding a political solution that
will restore peace to a country where violence seems endemic, and which has
been without a government since January 1991.
The United Nations chaired conference that opens in Addis Ababa today is a
belated start to what will be a long and arduous process. But it is far from
certain that the UN, deeply discredited in Somalia by the inept handling
initially of the relief operation, has either the organisational capacity or
the political credibility to play the role it has assumed.
The conference opens under inauspicious circumstances. President George
Bush's new year visit to Mogadishu left fundamental questions about US
policy unresolved. The hostile reception accorded Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali,
the UN secretary-general, in Mogadishu yesterday illustrated some of the
difficulties he faces when presiding over today's conference, where he will
be seeking to establish himself as a trusted mediator.
From the beginning of the military intervention in Somalia, it has been
clear that getting food to the starving citizens was not in itself enough.
Food warehouses have to be guarded, convoys protected, distribution centres
kept secure, the safety of aid workers assured and  - most difficult of all
 -the warlords and their gangs either disarmed or disciplined.
US role
Only the US has the resources to mount and sustain an operation on the scale
required, yet Washington's view of its role falls short of UN expectations,
and the timetable and the full extent of its commitment is uncertain.
Washington has refused to respond to Mr Boutros Ghali's call to intervene in
the conflict by disarming the gangs of gunmen responsible for the pillaging
of food. The sole function of the troops so far has been to ensure that food
reaches its destination.
All too often this has been a hollow achievement, for no sooner have the
troops departed than gunmen move in. And the need to make conditions safer
for aid workers was tragically underlined over the weekend with the murder
of Mr Sean Devereux, while working for Unicef in the southern Somali port of
Kismayu.
Regrettably during his two-day visit Mr Bush gave uncertain signals about US
intentions. At one meeting the president told aid workers that the US would
not leave Somalia 'in the lurch'. A few hours later Mr Bush was reassuring
US troops that Washington did not have an open-ended commitment to the
country. That is not expected of him: but a clearer indication of US policy
is overdue.
As it is, his comments are incompatible, and reflect the ambivalence that
has marked Operation Restore Hope from the start. No one now expects the
outgoing US administration to clarify its position; but it must urgently be
addressed when Mr Clinton take office later this month.
Military commitment
Only a firm long-term US military commitment to Somalia will concentrate the
minds of the dozen political parties attending today's conference. Nothing
in the record of the two dominating figures, Somalia's self-styled president
Ali Mahdi Mohamed, and Mohamed Farah Aideed, suggests they genuinely have
their country's interests at heart. Their fratricidal dispute has destroyed
Mogadishu, and few Somalis have any faith that their handshake of
reconciliation last month will be binding.
When the warlords are controlled, the negotiating process set in train at
Addis Ababa can become more representative. The existing participants
represent too narrow a range of interests. A broader cross-section is
needed, ranging from exiles to elders, academics and former politicians,
many of whom are unable to leave Somalia or are reluctant to take part in
politics while the gunmen hold sway.
Only when legitimate political and community leaders gather round the
conference table can reconciliation and recovery get under way. Unless
Washington helps the UN rein in the warlords, the peace process will not get
off the ground.
</TEXT>
