<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Observer: Pecking order
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Who gets what in the new year honours list has always been a bit of a
mystery especially when it comes to honouring Britain's captains of finance
and commerce. Indeed, this year's crop of Ks will have done little to
disabuse those who feel that contributions to Tory party coffers remain far
more important than success on the business pitch.
Admittedly, the latest bunch seemed more deserving than some. TI's
Christopher Lewinton, Kingfisher's Geoffrey Mulcahy, HSBC's Willie Purves
and LWT's Christopher Bland are above average business leaders. Meanwhile,
Harry Djanogly and Raymond Johnstone, are of the old school of successful
businessmen who regard charity and public service just as important as
making money.
However, if 'Chips' Keswick of Hambros deserves a knighthood for 'services
to banking', surely Brian Pitman, the long serving chief executive of Lloyds
Bank - Britain's most successful big bank - also deserves the same sort of
recognition. He has done more than most to revolutionise the efficiency of
British banking.
