<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Observer: Yesterday's man
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ever since Bob Heller gave up running Management Today, the flagship
magazine in Michael Heseltine's Haymarket Publishing Group, Britain's top
management magazine has been turning over its editors faster than most
companies change finance directors.
However, Tom Lloyd's tenure in the editorial chair - a mere 10 weeks - must
set some sort of record for short service. Lloyd, who has written several
management books and edited the now defunct Financial Weekly, told the UK
Press Gazette that he didn't feel that he 'had a mandate to edit'.
Admittedly, the recession has taken a heavy toll on business magazines, but
Lloyd's departure doesn't seem to have been linked to poor financial
performance. Rather it sounds as if he was slow in making the sort of
changes that his new masters wanted.
Dennis Hackett, the new editor, is a veteran magazine man rather than
management guru. He has edited Queen and Nova, and relaunched several
well-known magazines including Tatler, where Tina Brown first made her name.
Indeed, he tells me that he was the one who hired her.
</TEXT>
