<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Letter: Long-term savings in danger of tax discrimination
within EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr DAVID R F SIMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Although the EC single market has now arrived and regulatory barriers
to trade in financial services between member states have disappeared, it
seems that trade in long-term retail savings will continue to be restricted
by discriminatory tax. Thus the benefits of the single market will not
extend to the long-term savings of the Community's households.
Long-term savings are a big part of the financial services sector. It has
been estimated that there may be Ecu700bn of assets in the balance sheets of
pension funds within the EC, and a further Ecu850bn in the funds of life
assurance companies. According to the Cecchini Report, about one third of
benefits arising from the single market were expected to come from the
liberalisation of financial services.
When the single market was launched in 1986 the retail savings industry was
tightly enclosed within each state's own markets. In rare cases where
cross-border trade was not explicitly prohibited by statute or by exchange
control, it was ruled out by discriminatory tax provisions. For example, in
the UK the benefits of long-term savings contracts issued to UK residents by
non-resident insurance companies are more heavily taxed than are the
benefits of similar policies issued by UK insurance companies.
Most member states of the Community have similar discriminatory taxation.
While differences in tax rates between countries do not create barriers to
trade, discriminatory rates do. Yet, while the single market programme has
removed regulatory barriers, nothing has been done to tackle the continuing
existence of the discriminatory tax barriers to trade in long-term retail
savings.
Indeed, a European Court decision in February (Bachmann decision) appears to
uphold the right of member states to discriminate against foreign savings
contracts.
Worse, an amendment to the Treaty of Rome - article 73D - introduced at
Maastricht appears further to legitimise such discrimination.
Unless the Council of Ministers is prepared to act, the Community will be
seen to have failed to complete an important part of the single market
programme. Such a failure will not be marginal: it was precisely from the
liberalisation of the long-term retail savings sector that a large part of
the benefit of the single market was expected to arise.
David R F Simpson,
economist,
The Standard Life Assurance Company,
3 George Street, Edinburgh
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
