<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Letter: Poland in the EC essential for European peace and
unity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JULIAN ROCHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, In the aftermath of the Edinburgh summit and enthusiasm over the
timetable of accession of western countries such as Austria and Norway to
the EC, another subject slipped off the agenda - a firm timetable for the
accession of Poland, and indeed then Hungary and the Czech and Slovak
republics to the EC. This is now a matter for Copenhagen.
Economists at the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development have
already made the important point that if the EC's governments made the
decision, these countries could be admitted right away. Poland's democracy
is no more fragile than that of some existing EC members. Moreover, it is a
rapidly maturing one - as well as being an economy that will actually grow
this year. Convergence criteria are in the eye of the beholder; to insist
that these countries meet necessary economic and political pre-conditions
before they accede could prove to be the most awful short-sightedness.
Britain's prime minister, Mr John Major, has said that nothing would give
him greater pleasure than to see Poland become a member of the EC. There is
no recession so severe, no problem of economic integration so serious, that
cannot be overcome to achieve a degree of European unity that may prove
essential for the peace, the development, and, eventually, the prosperity
also of Europe as a whole.
Ask not what Poland must do for the EC, but instead what all in the EC must
do for Poland.
Julian Roche,
research secretary,
The Bow Group,
Langley House,
Ashley Common Road,
New Milton, Hampshire
</TEXT>
