<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 93 / Arts: Opera's daring annus mirabilis / A look back at a year
of adventurous productions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The operatic talking point of 1992 was, strictly speaking, a non-artistic
one: the prominence given to the Royal Opera House and its general director,
Jeremy Isaacs, in a run of sensationalised media stories in the middle of
the year. These were variants on the theme of 'Opera House deficit scandal:
Isaacs blamed for chaos', which had been developed on the basis of leaks of
supposed excerpts from the Arts Council report into the house, chaired by
Baroness Warnock.
Who did the leaking has never been established. The excerpts came wrapped in
unattributed comment and fake-impartial tones of delivery. Their purpose
seemed designed to stir public outcry prior to the Covent Garden board's
re-examination of Mr Isaacs's contract. (In the end, he got it renewed until
1995.)
At one point, indeed, it was 'widely rumoured that David Mellor is looking
round for a replacement', according to a Times Diary item; that it was not
his job to do so left the rumour-mongers unruffled. All of this unfolded
during the summer of David Mellor's brief occupancy of the heritage
ministry. His eventual resignation, on September 24, was of course one of
the bigger national news items of the year, and its effects and implications
were felt far more widely than in the opera world alone.
Mellor constantly denied that he was in any way responsible for the
Isaacs-destabilisation campaign. It does seem, then, an extraordinary
coincidence that since his departure a blanket of silence should have
descended so completely on the whole subject. (In the event, what little of
the report was eventually disclosed offered no opinion of Isaacs's
managerial skills; its main criticisms - ridiculously short-sighted, in my
view - were directed at the ROH redevelopment scheme.)
To Royal Opera House-watchers the irony in all this was that a distasteful
brouhaha should have been stirred up in the year that was, by general
consent, artistically the most rewarding for a very long time. Of the eight
new productions already unveiled (I write prior to the opening night of the
ninth, Alcina), only one elicited a wide range of critical catcalls. This
was the house's tribute to the Rossini bicentenary in the form of a
hideously over-designed, feebly farcical, vocally underpowered Viaggio a
Reims.
But it is worth recalling the others, not only for the happy memories they
summon but because they added up to so richly varied and balanced a
repertory. For me the peak of excitement was reached by the first house
production of Prokofiev's Fiery Angel, an uneven opera made enthralling by
Edward Downes's lucidly controlled conducting, the singing of the Russians
Galina Gorchakova (a young soprano of thrilling potential) and Sergey
Leiferkus, and the 'nave' theatrical vision of the producer, David Freeman,
in which weird, beautiful flesh was given to the demons haunting the opera.
But the triumphant London re-creation of Glyndebourne's epoch-making 1986
Porgy and Bess, with Andrew Litton its inspired conductor, came near it. So
did Death in Venice in Colin Graham's shimmering, liquidly unfolded staging,
with Philip Langridge its masterly Aschenbach. The manifold musical
pleasures of a Bellini Puritani sung with beauty of tone and style and
potent dramatic feeling by June Anderson and Giuseppe Sabbatini were
complemented by a handsome, intelligent production.
Don Giovanni, with Thomas Allen at the head of a uniformly fine cast, was
given a dark, complex, violent-spirited reading by Johannes Schaaf that
argued its case with impressive clarity. Bernard Haitink's rapturously warm,
unforced conducting of Die Frau ohne Schatten and Anna Tomova-Sintov's
noble, heartfelt Empress were the notable features of the colourful but
somewhat limited Cox-Hockney production. In a Flying Dutchman (staged by Ian
Judge) more notable for splashy stage effects than deep re-examination of
Wagner's themes and characters, overall standards were high, and there was
the inestimable bonus of Julia Varady's gloriously impulsive, vocally
italianate Senta.
The improvement of the chorus continued apace. On the whole, revivals were
carefully considered. The return of the 1990 Guillaume Tell, enriched with
previously missing authority, gave this Rossini appassionato particular
satisfaction; the polished bel canto of Alfredo Kraus and Sumi Jo in
L'elisir d'amore afforded a collector's item; and while I found the
ballyhooed Otello - it marked Georg Solti's 80th birthday, brought back
Placido Domingo and Kiri Te Kanawa, and featured Leiferkus's first Iago -
coolly calculated and unmoving, it was plainly the product of a front-rank
opera-theatre.
A further irony of this splendid year is that it directly bears out one of
the subsidiary Warnock criticisms: that the company has been favouring
artistic adventurousness over economically prudent planning (which would
give us Carmen, Boheme, Tosca and Barber wall to wall). In the words of the
November editorial of Opera magazine, 'In effect the ROH is being castigated
for doing its job - staging world-class performances of opera and dance - in
open defiance of an Arts Council that is plainly not doing its job ie
funding it.'
But with the Royal Opera now committed to putting into practice several of
Warnock's recommendations; with one cancellation - La Juive - already
announced and perhaps others to follow; and with the Arts Council's 2.5 per
cent rise in funding allocation just settled, there is every depressing
chance that 1992 will have been the last such annus mirabilis of Royal Opera
achievement for some while to come.
The big news from the English National Opera this year was that the
government produced Pounds 12.8m to enable the company to buy the Coliseum
from Stoll Moss. Security of tenure is undoubtedly a boon. I trust it will
enable the new team poised to succeed Messrs Jonas, Elder and Pountney at
the end of the 1992-93 season to take a long view of planning - opera
invariably suffers from its lack.
I am not sure whether it was this, or the need for programming caution after
the bold, risky 1990-91 season of 20th-century opera, that seemed to leave
in its wake great tranches of 'safe' Mikado, Rigoletto and Magic Flute
revivals; but 1992 felt like a year of ENO batteries running down. There
were fewer new productions than in the past; their choice may have been
imaginative - Humperdinck's Konigskinder (an underrated, beautiful
late-Romantic fairy-tale which I particularly welcomed), Don Carlos, The
Force of Destiny, Princess Ida, and Janacek's Broucek - but all were to a
greater or lesser extent flawed by their production conceits or execution.
In the matter of Ken Russell's grotesquely vulgar, wretchedly incompetent
account of the Gilbert and Sullivan, the phrase 'greater extent' counts as
the most timorous of understatements.
Nicholas Hytner's eagerly awaited return to the house with The Force of
Destiny elicited a curiously muted Verdi encounter: fine performances from
Josephine Barstow and Jonathan Summers, serious Verdi conducting from Elder,
excessive reliance on the stage revolve. From the evidence of Pountney's
Konigskinder, Don Carlos and Broucek stagings, all replete with 'house
mannerisms', I suspect that he has reached something of an artistic
watershed, and that his forthcoming departure from Coliseum management will
occur not a moment too soon in his own artistic development.
The world premiere of John Buller's Bakxai - musically fascinating,
dramatically inert - was a duty conscientiously discharged. In the end it
was left to the vital, purposeful revivals of Xerxes (pure Hytner delight),
Street Scene, the Monteverdi Orfeo and Wozzeck to remind us of ENO's past
form when operating on full engine-power.
Opera North's choice of repertory seemed to me an ideal mixture of adventure
and intelligent renewal: Schreker's Ferne Klang, The Thieving Magpie (apart
from the London Tell, the only really worthwhile Rossini centenary tribute
in all our opera theatres), a Boris Godunov revival, the first British
staging of Gerhard's 1949 Duenna (which followed hard on the first-ever
staging, in Madrid), Orpheus in the Underworld, Billy Budd. The success rate
varied, but the excitement of visiting this admirable company was never
seriously confounded; and, in the case of the shattering Budd, reality far
surpassed expectation.
Welsh National Opera put on what many people seem to consider the operatic
highlight of the year: the Pelleas collaboration between Pierre Boulez and
Peter Stein. On this page Andrew Clements pronounced the Cardiff opening a
'landmark'; I had the misfortune to hit upon a later performance dogged by
technical mishap; but over Boulez's Debussy conducting there could be no
grounds for dispute: it was magnificent tout court.
WNO's Elektra, in a David Alden production that with its panoply of stale
surrealist gestures looked like a David Alden parody, had the benefit of
Felicity Palmer's star-quality Clytemnestra; Gluck's Iphigenie en Tauride
was also done in a modish, arty way but with intensity, urgency and
commitment.
Scottish Opera dipped a toe into the waters of
modern-production-with-a-vengeance with a Handel Julius Caesar styled (and
musically re-written) after the model of Viz comics. I thought it beneath
contempt. In general, hopes for a revival of this company's artistic
fortunes were greatly increased by the appointment of Richard Armstrong to
succeed John Mauceri as music director. If anyone still needed evidence of
Armstrong's mature mastery, the spellbinding Edinburgh Festival concert
performance of Schoenberg's Moses and Aaron came usefully to hand.
In the domain of new opera it was not a significant year for Britain. Bakxai
apart, the most notable premiere was the Women's Theatre Trust staging of
Nicola Lefanu's Blood Wedding - notable, that is, for the startling
disproportion between staging (classy) and work itself (thin gruel). I went
to Chicago for Bolcom's McTeague, a mixture of 'modern' and 'popular' idioms
imperfectly coalesced but with beguiling moments; and to Los Angeles, where
the Finnish National Opera gave the premiere of Aulis Sallinen's fourth
opera Kullervo. My admiration for this composer's theatrical vision,
unremittingly stark yet 'approachable', was not unanimously shared; but for
the great Finnish baritone Jorma Hynninen in the title role, superlatives
were unleashed on every side. When - we ask again - is he to receive an
invitation from Covent Garden?
The last word must go to Glyndebourne. This was its final season in the 'old
house'; already during the festival a huge excavation was visible where the
walled garden used to be. This year there is no festival; the year after,
there is the promise of a new theatre larger than the old (but not
un-intimately so), and with warmer acoustics and greater audience comfort as
its goals.
The final summer series before the break was one of tremendous achievement.
Revivals of Cos fan tutte, Jenufa (altogether triumphant) and Death in
Venice offered examples of the Glyndebourne 'work ethic' at its most
elevated. The new Peter Grimes, conducted by Andrew Davis and produced by
Trevor Nunn in carefully researched naturalistic vein, may not have pulled
its component parts exactly into balance - and those Suffolk accents were
definitely an error of judgment - but there were many musical and dramatic
illuminations to compensate.
The new Queen of Spades, conducted by Davis and produced by Graham Vick, was
a revelation. It was at once contemporary in dramatic idiom and capable of
richly affectionate spectacle, turbulent and colourful; and it was sung -
by, among others, Nancy Gustafson, Felicity Palmer, Sergey Leiferkus, Dmitry
Kharitonov, and the alarmingly unsparing Yury Maruzin as Hermann - with a
truly Tchaikovskyan blend of poetry and passion.
It formed one of the peaks of Glyndebourne achievement, and an inspired
climax to one of the most impressive festivals in Glyndebourne history. If I
had a prize to award for 'event of the year', this Queen of Spades would
unquestionably be its recipient.
</TEXT>
